<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Presence Threatens Security in Gulf: Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The military presence of the United
States is the real threat to the security in the Persian Gulf, said
Acting Commander-in-Chief Gholamali Rashid of Iran's armed forces
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It is the physical and military presence of the U.S.,
especially their battleships armed with weapons of mass destruction
and nuclear weapons, that threatens the security of the region,"
the major general said, quoted by the official IRNA News Agency.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with Omani Air Force Commander Muhammed Bin
Mahfooz Al-Arezi, the military leader said the U.S. is trying to
rule over the energy sources of the region perpetually.
</P>
<P>
Refuting Washington accusations that Iran threatens the Gulf
security, he said that on the contrary Iran is seeking to
strengthen its ties with its southern Gulf neighbors, Oman in
particular.
</P>
<P>
Iran's policy of detente is not merely a tactical one but a
strategic decision, he added, noting that Iran makes no distinction
between its own security and that of the regional countries.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted the visiting Omani air force commander as describing
his visit to Iran useful. Al-Arezi said Iran has high military
capabilities, and invited Iran to share its defense experiences
with Oman.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Rashid and Al-Azeri also signed a
bilateral defense agreement on Monday whose contents were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The high-level Omani delegation ended a four-day visit on
Monday. Iran and Oman face each other across the strategic Strait
of Hormuz at the mouth of the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
They signed an agreement in November 1998 allowing their
military experts to be present at each other's annual military
exercises as observers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
