<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Speaks Highly of China's Support to G-77 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Cuba Monday spoke highly of China'
s support to the Group of 77 and contribution to the convocation
of the South Summit, the largest gathering of heads of state and
government since the founding of the body in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Foreign Minister Felipe Perez Roque told a press
conference here that the presence of the Chinese delegation means
a strong support of China to G-77.
</P>
<P>
"China can play a very important role for the Group of 77," he
said. "Given its high degree of economic and social development in
a socialist system, which is also a great encouragement for our
effort as a group of Third World countries."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation, headed by Vice Premier Li Lanqing, is
expected to arrive in Havana, the Cuban capital, Tuesday afternoon.
China, which is not a member of the body, has always supported the
just stance and reasonable demand of G-77 and it has been long in
close and friendly ties with the organization.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban foreign minister made the remarks as world leaders
are arriving in the Caribbean island country for the South Summit,
which ends on April 14.
</P>
<P>
A total of 122 delegations are attending the South Summit, and
60 countries will be represented by heads of state or government,
the foreign minister said, adding that also present at the first
summit of G-77 are 34 delegations of non-member countries and
representatives of 35 international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Covering the historic event are 500 correspondents from 80
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The organization was founded by 77 developing countries in
Geneva on June 15, 1964. Although the membership of G-77 has
increased to 133 countries, the original name was retained because
of its historic significance.
</P>
<P>
As the largest Third World coalition in the United Nations and
the largest grouping in the South, G-77 provides the means for the
developing world to articulate and promote its collective economic
interests and enhance its joint negotiating capacity on all major
international economic issues in the United Nations system, and
promote economic and technical cooperation among developing
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
