<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Flies to Cuba for South Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking to the press at Madrid Airport en route to Havana
earlier Monday, Annan said there were some positive lessons that
developing countries could share with each other, including in
information technologies.
</P>
<P>
"We need to use information technology and computers to be able
to leapfrog all the difficult developmental stages that other
countries went through," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides addressing the summit Wednesday, the U.N. chief is
expected to conduct bilateral meetings withe several of the heads
of state and government in attendance of the gathering of the
Group of 77, a U.N. spokesman told reporters in New York.
</P>
<P>
The meeting scheduled for Wednesday and Thursday will focus on
globalization, knowledge and technology, South-South cooperation
and North-South relations.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 77 was created on 15 June 1964 when developing
countries adopted a joint declaration at the conclusion of the
first session of the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Currently, it consists of 133 developing countries from Africa,
Asia and Latin America, with Nigeria as chairman for the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Foreign Minister Calls for Globalization of Solidarity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The foreign minister told a press conference here that the
economy imposed by the developed world today is excluding the poor,
which make for the vast majority of the planet, while denying
their access to development.
</P>
<P>
"It is to solve this situation that we stand for dialogue"
between the North and the South, he said. "We need a North-South
dialogue in which the North listens to our opinions."
</P>
<P>
However, such a dialogue, he said, "must be conducted on an
equal footing for both North and South, bearing in mind all of our
interests, especially our fundamental right to development."
</P>
<P>
In that regard, he said he is highly optimistic about the South
Summit, in progress here through April 14, for this meeting is
taking place on very appropriate timing, in the year when the
United Nations is summoning the so called "the Millennium Assembly,
" where the international policies of the next century will be
devised.
</P>
<P>
But he said "because the South cannot wait for ever, as it
needs an urgent solution to its problems, and the North cannot
expect the South to tackle all problems on its own. They must be
worked out in a joint manner."
</P>
<P>
Currently, the inhabitants of the rich countries, which account
for some 20 percent of the world's total population, enjoy 80
percent of the wealth available to the world, he said, adding that
this is "unbearable" in the current international financial
situation.
</P>
<P>
He charged "a few countries" with an attempt to impose their
political views, which usually respond to their economic polices
as well, on the rest of the world at the U.N., invoking the so-
called "right to humanitarian intervention," in violation of the
principle of non-interference in another country's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
What would happened, he asked, if countries of the South would
form an alliance to bomb the North just because countries there
are practicing xenophobia or abusing the rights of minorities?
</P>
<P>
"The only acceptable invasion for us," he added half-jokingly,
would be one that brings lower interests for long-term financing.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister made the remarks as the Group of 77 is
convening the South Summit, the largest gathering of heads of
state and government since the founding of the body in June 1964.
</P>
</TEXT>
