<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Heated Debate Expected on Trade in Endangered Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Li Jinqi
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Heated and even emotional debates
are expected on international trade in endangered species as some
2,000 delegates across the world converged in the Kenyan capital
Nairobi to begin an international meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the 11th Meeting of the Conference of Parties of the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES),
which was opened on Sunday and hosted by the United Nations
Environmental Program (UNEP) at its headquarters, 62 proposals
mainly focused on trade in endangered species will be discussed
among the delegates from more than 100 nations.
</P>
<P>
"Our discussions on elephants, whales, sharks and sea turtles
are, I am sure, going to be difficult and heated, sometimes even
emotional," said CITES Secretary-General Willem Wijinstekers in
his opening statement for the 11-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that one of the most high-profile issues on
the CITES agenda for the current meeting is the possible
introduction of another sale of ivory from southern African
countries.
</P>
<P>
At the previous CITES meeting in Harare, Zimbabwe, in 1997, it
was agreed that Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe could make a
one-time and highly- controlled experimental sale of their
existing ivory stock to Japan. These countries sold a total of 49
tons of tusks to Japan last year.
</P>
<P>
At the present meeting, the three countries, together with
South Africa, proposed a further authorization for trading
elephant products under strictly controlled conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenya and India posed a tit-for-tat to their proposal
and advocated a complete ban on ivory trade, fearing that the
experimental sale would result in further ruthless elephant
poaching that has been alarming in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Both Kenya and India are expected to rally delegates to vote
for the reinstating of the elephant species to the CITES Appendix
I which bans all trade, while several southern African countries
will surely seek to push the case to Appendix II that regulates
trade under a strict monitoring system, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 Kenyan youths Sunday afternoon gathered at the UNEP
gate, holding placards or slogans against the lifting of the ban
on ivory trade.
</P>
<P>
Another highly charged issue at the CITES meeting, which will
inevitably arouse fervent debate, is the trade in whale products
as Japan and Norway proposed a restart of limited hunting of gray
and minke whales.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Norway believe that certain stock of gray and minke
whales are healthy enough to be transferred from CITES Appendix I
to Appendix II that regulates trade through the issue of hunting
permits.
</P>
<P>
However, the World Wildlife Foundation recommended that the
proposal by Japan and Norway be rejected as it was at the 1997
CITES meeting, arguing that any discussion about rules for
controlling whaling must take place in the International Whaling
Commission.
</P>
<P>
All commercial whaling has been banned by the International
Whaling Commission since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Also among the 62 proposals is that on the resumption of a
limited trade in hawksbill turtle shells as Cuba wants to make a
single, internationally supervised sale to Japan of up to 6,900
kilograms of shells from its existing stock, followed by an annual
trade quota.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that some nations, in proposing the relaxation
of the current trade bans, insist that the move would not harm the
overall populations of the endangered species and should even help
them in the long term if quotas are applied and the sales closely
monitored.
</P>
<P>
But conservationists and some governments said that these
proposals would either bring massive violation of quota
arrangement or stimulate an illegal trade, leading to the species
decimation or outright disappearance.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Fund for Animal Welfare,
thousands of species in the world are endangered as a result of
human activities such as hunting, habitat destruction and
pollution.
</P>
<P>
CITES was established in 1975 in order to address the threat
posed by international trade in endangered species. To date, 151
countries and regions have become parties to the treaty, making it
one of the world's most important agreements on wildlife
protection.
</P>
<P>
So far, the CITES agreement offers varying degrees of
protection to more than 30,000 species of plants and animals,
depending on their conditions in the wild and the effect that
international trade may have on their survival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
