<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Economy Grows by 2.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran's gross national product (GNP)
grew by 2.4 percent in the last Iranian calendar year that ended on
March 19, said Governor of the Central Bank Mohsen Nourbakhsh on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not specify the real value of GNP. Commerce
Minister Mohammad Shariatmadari said last month that Iran's annual
gross domestic product (GDP) is around 120 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iran's foreign trade balance was positive last year, with
exports and imports increasing 9 percent and 14 percent
respectively, Nourbakhsh was quoted by the official Islamic
Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the total oil revenues topped 16 billion U.S. dollars
last year due to the rising of oil prices, which was the major push
for the economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil exports (including engineering services) stood at 3.5
billion dollars last year, registering a 8.5 percent rise compared
to the year before. The value of imports stood at 12.3 billion
dollars in the period.
</P>
<P>
Iran's total foreign debts last year declined by 25 percent to
stand at 10.5 billion dollars as a result of the positive trade
balance, Nourbakhsh said.
</P>
<P>
The budget showed no deficit last year, with the total hard
currency sources equaling the consumption of 19.77 billion dollars.
Inflation rate was 20.1 percent last year, almost the same level as
the year before, the official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
