<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Committed to Regional Peace and Stability: Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
is committed to regional and international peace and security,
said visiting U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived here Monday morning from Saudi Arabia, told a
press conference that his talks with UAE President Sheikh Zayed Al-
Nahyan and other senior UAE officials had covered bilateral
relations and a wide range of regional and global issues.
</P>
<P>
"The security relationship between the U.S. and the UAE is very
good and getting better," said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his pleasure with UAE's decision to purchase the U.
S. F-16 fighters, saying the decision would further strengthen
security cooperation between the two countries and enhance security
and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
While addressing concerns that the deal may encourage arms race
in the region, Cohen said "We think every nation is entitled to
provide for its security needs and the UAE has considered several
options before deciding the F-16 was the best aircraft."
</P>
<P>
On Iran, Cohen said the U.S. was encouraged by the recent
political developments in Iran.
</P>
<P>
"But, the U.S. is yet to see changes in the unacceptable Iranian
policy in their support for terrorism, their attempts to undermine
the Middle East peace and the development of weapons of mass
destruction,"said Cohen, affirming that such changes would benefit
all countries in the region by creating a great sense of security.
</P>
<P>
As for Iraq, Cohen said "We agreed that (Iraqi President) Saddam
Hussein can end the suffering of Iraqi people by complying with the
U.N. Security Council resolutions and until he complies, sanctions
must continue."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under crippling U.N. sanctions since 1990 when its
troops invaded Kuwait which triggered the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"Now, Iraq is trying to ease the impact of the sanctions by
smuggling more oil,"said the U.S. defense chief. Iraq has been
banned from selling oil on world market under the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Cohen charged that Saddam has been using revenues of smuggled
oil to build palaces and military projects. "He may be accumulating
as much as a billion dollars annually through this illegal
smuggling."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Iran announced Sunday that Iranian Revolutionary
Guards seized a tanker suspected of carrying smuggled oil from Iraq
in defiance of U.N. sanctions and this may signal a crackdown by
Iran on these illegal operations.
</P>
<P>
The UAE, he said, supports the U.N. operations to halt smuggling
of Iraqi oil.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question whether the U.S. demand for lower oil
prices can affect U.S. arms sales to oil producers in the region,
Cohen said "I don't believe their will be any major impact on the
needs of the countries to modernize their armed forces," adding
that higher oil prices could affect global economy.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is currently on a tour of the Middle East countries. The
trip has taken him to Israel, Egypt, Jordan, Qatar, Bahrain and
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Cohen will leave here for Oman later on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
