<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Calls for Efforts to Activate Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat urged the international community to
exert more effective efforts to push forward the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the appeal during a joint press conference with
visiting Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien after their talks at
the Palestinian presidential office here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The second round of Palestinian-Israeli peace talks going on in
Washington failed to yield any positive result so far, Arafat said,
adding "we insist on the demand for an effective U.S., European and
Arab roles in the talks."
</P>
<P>
On Jewish settlement expansion, Arafat said it was illegal and
went against the U.N. Security Council resolutions as well as
against the clear-cut international positions and Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
The settlements and Jerusalem are among the key thorny issues in
the final-status talks, he added, noting that the U.S.
administration believed settlement activities would sabotage the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said his talks with Chretien "were positive, important
and constructive." He added that the talks covered a wide range of
issues on top of which were the bilateral ties, especially in the
areas of education and technology.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side, according to Arafat, suggested the
formation of a joint Canadian-Palestinian permanent committee.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Chretien reaffirmed his country's support for the
Palestinian people and the PNA, especially in the economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Chretien, the highest level Canadian leader ever to visit
Palestine, said his minister of international trade would come here
on top of a senior economic delegation soon to coordinate Canadian
assistance to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He added that he discussed with Arafat the importance of
economic development for the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, Chretien underscored the
importance of unremitting international efforts to establish peace
in the region. "I felt a common Palestinian-Israeli desire to
activate the peace talks and serve the interests of the Palestinian
and Israeli peoples," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the issues of Jerusalem and refugees, the Canadian leader
said they should be solved through all-round talks.
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived at Gaza Strip Monday morning from Israel for a
short visit. He has flown back to Israel to continue official visit
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
