<HEADLINE> Turkish Police Arrest 17 Jihad Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkish security forces have
arrested 17 members of the outlawed fundamentalist terrorism
organization Jihad, including a leading member of Syrian origin,
said Ankara Police Bureau Chief Kemal Iskender on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Iskender told reporters that the security forces also seized two
rifles, four guns, bomb-making equipment, false identity cards, and
many documents and statements.
</P>
<P>
A week ago, police working in the Diskapi Hospital, affiliated
to the Social Security Agency (SSK), informed the Ankara Police
Bureau that two people who claimed to have been injured in a
traffic accident, applied to the hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
The two confessed during interrogation that they had planted 10
pipe bombs at various locations in Ankara. And they were injured
when one of the bombs exploded.
</P>
<P>
They said that their Jihad organization was influenced by the
ideas and principles of the Al-Jihad Organization in Egypt, which
was blamed for the assassination of former Egyptian President Anwar
Sadat in 1981.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the fundamentalist group seeks to establish
an Islamic-ruled state in Turkey by Jihad, giving priority to "
Jihad and politics."
</P>
<P>
The Ankara police chief said that they were recruiting
supporters, providing false identity cards and passports to their
militants to send them to foreign countries to receive military and
political trainings.
</P>
<P>
The organization was mainly centered in Ankara, but it also had
some supporters in southeastern Sanliurfa province.
</P>
<P>
The arrests were made as part of efforts by the Turkish
government to rein in terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of last year, Turkey has launched massive
crackdown on the radical Islamic terrorist group Hezbollah, which
seeks to turn secular but overwhelmingly Muslim Turkey into a
strict Islamic-ruled regime by resorting to violent means.
</P>
<P>
The group was found to have committed kidnappings, blackmail and
murders across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
