<HEADLINE> Door Still Open for Talks: Hoss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss
said Monday that the door is not closed for the resumption of the
peace talks with Israel, An Nahar newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Hoss made the remarks following a telephone discussion with
Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh, in which they discussed the
border flare-up and the upcoming summit between U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said that Lebanon prefers Israel's withdrawal from south
Lebanon with an agreement with Lebanon and its powerbroker Syria.
Lebanon, he reiterated, will not give a security guarantee to
Israel in the event of a unilateral withdrawal, because Israel
leaves unsolved a lot of thorny problems, such as Palestinian
refugees and the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.N. last week, President Emile Lahoud called on
the U.N. peacekeeping troops to disarm Palestinian force in refugee
camps who might try to launch attacks on Israel from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied a border enclave of 850 square kilometers in
south Lebanon in 1985 as a buffer zone against cross-border attacks
to its north.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state has decided to pull out its troops from south
Lebanon by July whatever an agreement with Syria and Lebanon is
reached or not.
</P>
<P>
The two Arab countries have stressed the simultaneity of two
tracks in peace negotiations with Israel. 
</P>
