<HEADLINE> EU Concerned About Situation in Congo, Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Monday
expressed its concern about the situation in the Democratic
Republic of Congo and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation bloc, at a monthly general affairs council of its
foreign ministers, urged all parties to the conflict in the
Democratic Republic of Congo to halt immediately all military
activities and respect in full their commitments made under the
Lusaka Agreement.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued after the first day of the two-
day council meeting, the EU foreign ministers said that the union
strongly supports the Lusaka Agreement and "stands ready to
continue to assist African efforts and to back the United Nations
in managing the crisis and in restoring peace and stability to the
Democratic Republic of Congo through political, diplomatic and
financial means."
</P>
<P>
The EU stressed that the ultimate responsibility for the
implementation of the Lusaka Agreement continues to rest with the
parties in the country, including assuring that conditions are in
place to enable the early deployment of the U.N. observer mission.
</P>
<P>
As for Zimbabwe, the European Union expressed readiness to send
observers for the planned elections which, one spokesman of the
two-day foreign ministers council meeting said, may help establish
democracy in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"If the elections are free and fair, they can be an opportunity
for the establishment of democracy," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the African country is willing to accept EU
observers for the elections, the spokesman said that there is
reason to believe that Zimbabwe is ready to accept. 
</P>
