<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Holds Meeting on Educational Trends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) began a five-day meeting here Monday on
lifelong learning in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of constant political, economic, environmental and
technological change in modern society, "there is every indication
that learning needs to become a lifelong function," according to a
background document prepared for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The report characterizes lifelong learning as "a survival issue
" and predicts that "the importance for persons to continue
learning throughout their active working life, and beyond, will
increasingly move to the top of individual, national and
international agendas in the future."
</P>
<P>
The report notes that at the all-important first step, the
primary school, an estimated "130 million children of primary
school age do not have access to basic education." Nearly two-
thirds of these children are girls.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, "close to one-sixth of the world's population is
unable to read and write," according to the report. The gender
imbalance in illiteracy levels means that "poor women are doubly
marginalized in terms of literacy through being both poor and
women."
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, delegates representing governments, private
employers, teachers' unions and non-governmental observers from
more than 50 countries will examine the funding, organization and
especially staffing options needed to address these problems and
gradually transform lifelong learning from "rhetoric" to "a
reality."
</P>
<P>
They will also study the development of linkages and strategic
partnerships between education and training institutes and
enterprises and the role of trade unions and employers in
fostering a culture of lifelong learning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
