<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abandonment of River Harnessing Works Responsible for Damage: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Prime Minister Mugur
Isarescu Monday stressed in the western city of Timisoara that the
abandonment of river harnessing works is responsible for the
damage caused by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Isarescu is now on a tour of the counties worst hit by
rainfalls in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said, "The civil protection investments have
to be correlated with the distressed areas. It is evident that we
have to invest more in the field but not only in sore spots but
also in the areas where we can create jobs. The start of several
projects without finishing them is extremely bad, even expensive."
</P>
<P>
"River harnessing works have been neglected in the past 10
years. Small sums were allocated and they are time consuming works,
but we hope that beginning next year we shall re-start the dam-
building process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Isarescu wanted to help notably the counties of Alba and
Hunedoara, central Romania, where unemployment is high. At the
first government meeting of this week, he is to make a first
assessment of the losses caused by the floods and will propose the
first measures to help the afflicted persons.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rainfall lately and the rapid melting of snow in the
first few days of April caused floods in most regions of the
country, with the center, the northwest and the southwest of
Romania being the most affected. The damage caused is considered
as the heaviest in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister of Civil Service Vlad Rosca, 489 villages
and towns were affected, most of them in Hunedoara and Caras-
Severin counties in western Romania. Another 14 were still
isolated by waters in Timis county, in western Romania too. In
Caras-Severin overflowing rivers inundated 1,013 households.
</P>
<P>
Rainfalls and storms blacked out 16 villages in Arad, Bihor and
Timis counties. Still under water are 85,273 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Romanian President Emil Constantinescu convened on April 12 an
emergency meeting of the country's Supreme Defense Council for an
analysis of the effects of the floods. The Supreme Defense Council
will set a medium- and long-term program for preventing floods and
ecological accidents and for improving the environment protection,
according to a Monday release of the Presidency's Press Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
