<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Negatively Affected by Rising Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Adjustments in international oil
prices have adversely affected economies like Zimbabwe which are
dependent on oil imports, said the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe in its
Economic Highlights released here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Sharp increases in oil prices imply that the terms of trade
have worsened, thus negatively impacting on the country's external
payments position," the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
"The latest round of increases in oil prices has meant that for
the same volume of oil imports, the country has had to finance
import bills close to three times its import bill in 1998," it
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, the cumulative effect of this
development includes imbalances in the country's balance of
payments and pressures on the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
This is particularly so in view of the country's continued poor
export performance, it said.
</P>
<P>
It commended the decision made by the Organization of Petroleum
 Exporting Countries to increase oil production by an additional
six percent.
</P>
<P>
The move should impact favorably on oil prices and dampen fuel
price induced inflationary pressures, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank also called for optimal and efficient use of fuel in
Zimbabwe, saying the practice would help stabilize the import
volumes of the country, minimizing the negative effects of the
latest round of fuel price increases.
</P>
<P>
The international oil prices rose from 12.1 U.S. dollars per
barrel at the beginning of 1999 to 25.6 U.S. dollars by the end of
the year and to 29 U.S. dollars by March 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
