<HEADLINE> Portugal, Angola Dispute Over Entry Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Portuguese government is
seeking clarification from Angola on refusal of entry of some 30
Portuguese citizens over the weekend, local informed sources said
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama was quoted as saying
that he had asked the Portuguese Embassy in Luanda "to insist on
clarification" of the two incidents which took place on Friday and
Sunday respectively, describing them as "unprecedented" and
"disagreeable".
</P>
<P>
"This situation does not appear compatible with the good level
of relations between our two countries," Gama said, adding that he
would contact his Angolan counterpart Joao Miranda.
</P>
<P>
However, spokesman for Angolan Foreign Ministry Antonio Pedro
downplayed the significance of the incidents, saying the
Portuguese-Angolan bilateral relations "are and will always be the
best. Everything else is speculation."
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic flap emerged last Friday when 12 Portuguese
citizens were denied entry into Angola by Luanda immigration
officials because they had come to Angola to work but only carried
visas for tourists, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
A similar incident took place on Sunday, when 15 Portuguese
were refused entry at the airport and sent back to Lisbon aboard a
TAP (Air Portugal) flight.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts noticed that the incidents followed the recent
bilateral tensions triggered by former Portuguese President Mario
Soares who publicly denounced "corruption" and "dictatorial"
practices in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Luanda government retorted immediately and charged Soares
for having benefitted from the Angolan rebels' illegal trade in
diamonds and ivory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
