<HEADLINE> SADC in Danger of Losing Workforce to AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Labor Minister Mario
Sevene on Monday said that the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) stands to lose its economically active
population in future if efforts to combat the AIDS epidemic are
not intensified.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Maputo at the opening of a meeting of the SADC
Employment and Labor Sector, Sevene suggested the drawing-up of
strategies for the preservation of human resources in face of the
threats posed by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
He added that another problem that faces SADC is child labor.
This is caused not only by poverty but also by the incapacity to
absorb children into education systems, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Sevene also said that labor migration within the community is
partly to blame for the poor development of SADC national
economics.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is a need to prioritize investment in the
health and education areas, and called on SADC member states to
undertake efforts leading to gender equality.
</P>
<P>
As regards Mozambique, Sevene said that, despite the
difficulties faced by the country in the wake of the devastating
flooding in February, the government is making efforts to
implement its five-year program, the top priority of which is to
eradicate absolute poverty.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, due to end on April 15, brings together SADC labor
 ministers and experts, as well as donor organizations.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that themes such as the SADC Employment and
Labor Sector Annual Report, the child labor problem, social
security, and the impact of AIDS on jobs, among others, will be
debated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
