<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Pressures Increase In Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The UK economy is experiencing
inflationary pressures, following an unexpectedly strong rise of
producer prices, according to official figures released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Output prices rose by 0.5 percent in March to an annual rate of
2.3 percent. It was the greatest monthly increase in nearly four
years since December 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile input prices, the cost of raw materials, rose even
faster, by 0.8 percent, to an annual rate of 13.6 percent on a
seasonally adjusted basis.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices are regarded to be the main reason for the rising
input prices that have increased by 134 percent year-on-year as
OPEC production cuts have led to a sharp increase in the price of
crude oil.
</P>
<P>
The Office of National Statistics (ONS) said that oil
contributed half (0.4 percent) of the total rise.
</P>
<P>
The ONS also said that 0.2 percent of the increase in output
prices was due to the effect of the Budget, which raised various
duties on tobacco, petrol, and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
While the UK economy is expected to grow strongly this year, by
around 3 percent, the news will put further pressure on the Bank
of England to raise interest rates again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
