<HEADLINE> Honda Extends Production Line In UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The UK car industry received a
much-needed boost with Japanese car firm Honda unveiling plans to
build a new model at its Wiltshire car plant.
</P>
<P>
Production of the four-wheel drive CR-V, currently build in
Japan, will start at Swindon in eight weeks time, following
exceptional demand for the car throughout Europe, said Honda
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Honda opened its factory at Swindon in 1992 and is currently
recruiting to boost the number of workers from the current 3,000
to about 4,000 by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month Honda announced a short-term cut back in
production at Swindon -- mainly because the plant is undergoing a
modernization program.
</P>
<P>
Honda said the news reaffirmed its long-term commitment to the
UK. The new model will be the fifth built at the plant.
</P>
<P>
Minoru Harada, chief executive of Honda's European operations,
said: "We are delighted that we will be building the CR-V at
Swindon to meet European customer demands."
</P>
<P>
"This manufacturing facility demonstrates the flexibility and
agility that characterizes Honda's success and confirms our long-
term commitment to making top quality cars in Britain," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
