<HEADLINE> Toronto's Worst Fire Brought Under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- After eight hours of fighting,
Canada's biggest city Toronto is bringing under control the most
dangerous fire the city has ever seen, said local media reports
Monday.
</P>
<P>
There have been no injuries. The city is yet to deal with
massive chemical aftermaths.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 firefighters and 30 fire trucks were battling
overnight to contain the spread of the worst fire started Sunday
afternoon in the eastern part of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
There were more explosions of tanks of inflammable liquids,
including xylene, a volatile hydrocarbon used as a solvent, at U.S.
E. Hickson Products plant located near Lawrence and Morningside
Aves, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters had difficulty getting close to four vats of
potentially explosive chemicals near where the fire continued to
burn out of control, Toronto Fire division commander Pat McCabe
said.
</P>
<P>
Environment Minister Dan Newman of Ontario was reported at the
scene Sunday night. He said monitoring trucks were called in to
test the surrounding atmosphere for toxins.
</P>
<P>
Huge black fumes were rising hundreds of meters into the sky
Sunday afternoon and could be seen as far away as Niagara-on-the-
Lake and the Burlington Skyway.
</P>
<P>
Several dozens of homes were evacuated, while nearby traffic
was halted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
