<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The following is a round-up of
Xinhua's archaeology news for the past week:
</P>
<P>
-- Heritage Law to Be Revised
</P>
<P>
China will revise its existing Heritage Law, which ensures
systematic heritage preservation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The State Council's Legislative Affairs Office has listed the
revision to the Heritage Law as a priority of its work this year.
The amendments will be submitted to China's top legislative body,
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, for
approval.
</P>
<P>
Rampant grave looting and relics smuggling have emerged in
recent years, and the existing law could not effectively curb such
crimes.
</P>
<P>
The amendments will also pave the way for coordinated
development plans between relics preservation authorities and the
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
-- Double City Walls Found in Ancient Emperor Tomb
</P>
<P>
Double city walls surrounding the tomb of the Emperor Gaozong
of the Tang Dynasty (618-907) were discovered recently.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists said that the tomb, 80 kilometers from Xi'an
City, capital of northwest Shaanxi Province, reflects the ancient
architectural style of imperial graves.
</P>
<P>
Aerial photography helped lead experts to the site. They
believe there are many treasures in the lavish tomb inside the
double city walls.
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient River Banks Found in Central Henan
</P>
<P>
Some remains of ancient banks of the River Luohe, near Luoyang
City of central Henan Province, were found recently.
</P>
<P>
The 400-meter river banks, dated back to the Sui (581-618) and
the Tang (618-907) dynasties, were important landmarks of the
ancient city of Luoyang, which was a state capital in many
dynasties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Sichuan to Build New Provincial Museum
</P>
<P>
Southwestern Sichuan Province is preparing to build a new
provincial museum capable of housing its 160,000 relics, including
five first-class national treasures.
</P>
<P>
The existing exhibition hall of the 60-year-old museum was
constructed in the early 1950s and is too small to accommodate the
province's store of relics.
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Private Kilns Found in Central Hubei
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists from central Hubei Province recently unearthed
more than 20 ancient kilns of the Song (960-1279) and Yuan (1271-
1368) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
The earthenware finds have both artistic and archaeological
value, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
-- Archaeological Report on Niya Expedition Published
</P>
<P>
The archaeological report from a Sino-Japanese expedition team
touring the Niya ruins in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region was
published recently in Urumqi, Xinjiang's capital.
</P>
<P>
The report provides readers with geological, hydrologic,
archaeological and anthropological information on Niya, an
isolated city of the 1,500-year-old Kingdom of Jingjue.
</P>
</TEXT>
