<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Minister Vows to Defend Press Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran's moderate Minister of Culture
and Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani on Monday vowed to defend
press freedom and make efforts to stop the trend of closing down
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Mohajerani said his ministry
would propose a bill to the new Majlis (parliament) to revise the
press law to annul the right of any state organs to revoke the
licenses of any newspapers.
</P>
<P>
"If a newspaper is found guilty, it could be punished by a
suspension of certain period, its license should not be revoked,"
he said, believing Iran's freedom-seeking press would feel more
comfortable after the reformists take over the parliament on May
27.
</P>
<P>
Iran's outgoing conservatives-dominated parliament has been
trying to put more restrictions on the press and it passed the
outlines of a bill to amend the press law last July, which
triggered a nationwide protest and a political turmoil following
clashes between students and policemen.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported that the conservatives intended to pass the
bill before handing over the parliament to the reformists, who
support freedom of the press and expression.
</P>
<P>
Iran's press, closely associated with political factions, went
through ups and downs in the past years. A total of 78 publications
were ordered to close in the capital in the past year alone.
</P>
<P>
In the past two weeks, four managing directors of reformist
newspapers have been summoned to the conservative courts for
questioning, and a number of journalists and writers interrogated.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of the official Islamic Republic News Agency
(IRNA) Fereydoun Verdinejad on Sunday openly called on the
government to safeguard the freedom of journalists.
</P>
<P>
"We should pay the price to foster openness in the society by
granting freedom to the journalists," he said after being called
before the press court for the second time in a week.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani said that the press court has the right to summon
managing directors of newspapers if complaints were filed against
their publications. But, he noted, summoning journalists or writers
is illegal, because managing directors should be responsible for
the contents of their newspapers.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that the appeals court has recently
confirmed a sentence of 30 months in prison on Mashaallah
Shamsolvaezin, editor-in-chief of the daily Asr-e Azadegan, for
press violations.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the press to observe the country's laws and
the limits of the press freedom, particularly before the reformists
take over the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
