<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate Approves E-commerce Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate approved
Monday on third and final reading a bill setting the legal
framework for the business transactions conducted through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
Voting 16-0, members of the senate stamped their approval for
the Electronic Commerce Act, an administrative measure certified
as among the urgent bills of the Estrada government.
</P>
<P>
Principally authored by Senate Science and Technology Committee
Chairman Ramon Magsaysay, the measure shall treat business
transactions performed through the computer as the regular course
of dealings that are backed by written documents.
</P>
<P>
Business transactions covered by the bill shall include
domestic and international exchange of information, dealings,
arrangements,agreements and contracts for procurement, payment,
supply management,transportation and facility operations.
</P>
<P>
"This proposed law will provide the necessary legal framework
for on-line business transactions to thrive in a dynamic
electronic environment," Magsaysay stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also said this will allow the small and medium entrepreneurs
in the country to become an equal player in an intensely-
competitive cybermarket. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
