<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Major Events in Inter-Korean Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Following are major events in
the economic ties between South Korea and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
-- October 7, 1988: South Korea announces permission of inter-
Korean trade.
</P>
<P>
-- January 21, 1989: Hyundai Group founder Chung Ju-yung
becomes the first South Korean businessman to visit the DPRK. He
signs a memorandum on the development of Mount Kumgang into a
tourist spot with the DPRK Asia-Pacific Peace Committee.
</P>
<P>
-- June 12, 1989: Guidelines on inter-Korean economic
cooperation are announced in a South Korean special presidential
decree.
</P>
<P>
-- August 1, 1990: South Korea makes law on inter-Korean
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- June 16, 1998: Chung Ju-yung leads 500 heads of cattle and
50 trucks into the DPRK through the truce village of Panmunjom and
agrees with the DPRK to develop tourism in Mount Kumgang.
</P>
<P>
-- August 6, 1998: Hyundai's business ventures in the DPRK gain
South Korean government's approval.
</P>
<P>
-- October 29, 1998: Chung Ju-yung visits the DPRK to meet DPRK
leader Kim Jong-il and secures long-term license on Mount Kumgang
development.
</P>
<P>
-- November 18, 1998: Hyundai launches first-ever sailing
cruise trip to Mount Kumgang.
</P>
<P>
-- February 4, 1999: Chung Ju-yung visits the DPRK and agrees
on farming cooperation and building a gymnasium in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
-- February 5, 1999: Hyundai establishes Hyundai Asia to
spearhead ventures in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
-- October 1, 1999: Chung Ju-jung and DPRK leader Kim meet for
a second time and agree on economic cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
