<HEADLINE> Cuba Extends Welcome to G-77 Summit Delegates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Cuba Monday expressed warm welcome
to delegations to the South Summit, the largest gathering of heads
of state and government since the 1964 establishment of the Group
of 77 (G-77), saying that the Caribbean country will do whatever
it can to ensure the success of the historic event.
</P>
<P>
Maria de Los Angeles, Cuba's vice minister of foreign affairs,
said at the opening session of the summit that the summit is the
highest-level meeting on Cuban soil, and she is confident that it
will achieve success.
</P>
<P>
"We have to see our Group of 77 as a vehicle. We will maintain
as a group in the international situation, and as the most
appropriate way to develop cooperation programs among ourselves,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"We are rich in human resources, "said the Cuban vice minister,
adding that it is hoped that G-77 will take advantage of the
resources available for the benefit of the peoples of the South.
</P>
<P>
The brief opening session, presided over by Chairman of G-77
Arthur Mbanefo, is designed to adopt agenda of the South Summit.
</P>
<P>
It will be immediately followed by a closed-door meeting of
senior officials from 133 G-77 member states to hammer out the two
final documents to be adopted at the end of the South Summit on
April 14.  
</P>
</TEXT>
