<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior G-77 Officials Hammer out Final Documents for South Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 77 (G-77) Monday held
a closed-door meeting of senior officials from its 133 member
states in the Cuban capital of Havana at the end of a brief
opening session of the South Summit, the largest gathering of
heads of state and government in the body's 36-year history.
</P>
<P>
The high-ranking officials kicked off the meeting at the Havana
International Conference Center to finish the last touch on the
two final documents which are to emerge from the Summit -- the
Joint Declaration and the Plan of Action.
</P>
<P>
The forward-looking Joint Declaration will set out a vision and
broad strategy for the future, while the Plan of Action will
clearly define the measures, targets and time frames for
implementation.
</P>
<P>
The two draft documents will be presented to foreign ministers
when they meet here Wednesday, and then be relayed to the heads of
state and government for approval when they meet for three days
beginning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two documents are expected to touch on the impact of
globalization on the developing world, how to better the South-
South cooperation, and how to improve the South-North dialogue,
including the access to market in developed countries, the
transfer of advanced science and technology and the relief of debt
burdens for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Maria de Los Angeles, Cuba's vice minister of foreign
affairs, expressed warm welcome to delegates to the South Summit,
saying that the Caribbean island country will make every possible
effort to ensure the historic event a success.
</P>
<P>
The South Summit, which is scheduled to conclude on April 14,
will mark a "turning point in the history of the Group of 77,"
Arthur Mbanefo, G-77 chairman and the Nigerian permanent
representative to the United Nations, told reporters here last
week.
</P>
<P>
Some 65 heads of state and government from Africa, Asia, Latin
American and the Caribbean are expected to attend the historic
event, along with representatives of more than 50 other countries,
such as China, and of 80 international organizations, including U.
N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The South Summit is an occasion for developing countries to
galvanize their strength and solidarity into a truly energetic
force against those capable of conditioning the international
economic order in which they must operate.
</P>
<P>
G-77 was founded on June 15, 1964 by 77 developing countries in
Geneva. Although its current membership has increased to 133
countries, the original name was retained because of its historic
significance.
</P>
<P>
As the largest Third World coalition in the United Nations and
the largest grouping in the South, the organization provides means
for the developing world to articulate and promote its collective
economic interests and enhance its joint negotiating capacity on
all major international economic issues in the United Nations
system, and promote economic and technical cooperation among
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
