<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Georgian President-Elect Eduard Shevardnadze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Veteran Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze won another five years in power in the Sunday
presidential election in the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
Eduard Shevardnadze, who was born on January 25, 1928 in a
teacher's family in the Mamati Lanchkhutsky region of the Georgian
Soviet Socialist Republic, became the president of Georgia in 1995
after serving as chairman of the republic's State Council since
1992.
</P>
<P>
He joined the Communist Party of the USSR in 1948 and graduated
from the Party School of the Central Committee of the Communist
Party of Georgia and the Kutasi Pedagogical Institute.
</P>
<P>
Between 1957-1961, he worked as first secretary of the Central
Committee of the Georgian Comsomol, then as a member of the
Central Committee of the Soviet Comsomol from 1958 to 1962 and as
first Communist Party secretary of the Mtskheta region from 1961
to 1963,
</P>
<P>
He was first deputy Public Order Minister of Georgia in 1964-65
and served as Georgia's minister of internal affairs from 1968 to
1972. His campaign against crime and political corruption caught
the attention of central government officials in Moscow, who named
him first secretary of the Georgian Communist Party in 1972.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze was elected first secretary the Tbilisi (Georgia's
capital) city committee of the Georgian Communist Party in 1972,
then served as first secretary of the Central Committee of the
party between 1972-1985.
</P>
<P>
He became member of the Central Committee of the Communist
Party of the Soviet Union (CPSU) in 1976, alternate member of the
Political Bureau of the CPSU in 1978, and was full member of the
bureau from 1985 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Shevardnadze was nominated Minister of Foreign Affairs
for USSR. His close personal and ideological ties to party
chairman Mikhail Gorbachev influenced his nomination. As foreign
minister, Shevardnadze oversaw a transformation of Soviet
international relations under the Gorbachev administration.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze was a strong supporter of the withdrawal of the
Soviet military from Afghanistan in 1989. He also promoted arms
reduction.
</P>
<P>
He served as foreign minister of the Soviet Union from July
1985 to December 1990 and was re-appointed Minister of Foreign
Relations of USSR on November 19, 1991.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, Shevardnadze was elected chairman of the State Council
of the newly independent Republic of Georgia. He was elected
chairman of the Civic Union of Georgia on November 21, 1993.
</P>
<P>
After Georgia's independence, Shevardnadze became deeply
involved in a dispute with separatists in the autonomous republic
of Abkhazia, located in the northwest portion of the country. To
gain Russian support in Abkhazia, Shevardnadze agreed to enroll
Georgia in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In August 1995, Georgia's legislature approved a new
Constitution, which restored the office of the presidency. Four
months later, he won the first Georgian general election with more
than 70 percent of the vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
