<HEADLINE> WSBI Asia-Pacific Regional Group Meeting Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The 6th Asia-Pacific Regional
Group Meeting of the World Saving Banks Institute (WSBI) opened in
Shanghai today to plan for future operations in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 specialists, including governors of savings banks
from WSBI Asian-Pacific member countries, and representatives of
WSBI Management Committee were in attendance.
</P>
<P>
De Noose, chairman of WSBI Management Committee, said WSBI has
been going all out to increase exchanges in information and
experiences among different areas, to promote cooperation among
members from different regions, and to help member banks with
their reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, bankers will discuss future plans
of WSBI in the Asian-Pacific region, the Asian economic status and
future prospects, challenges faced by saving banks, economic and
financial reforms in China, regional cooperation among banks from
different parts of China, and ways for savings banks to
participate in regional economic development.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1996 with headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, WSBI
consists of African, Asian-Pacific, American and European regional
groups and has 107 institutional members which represent 1,500
saving banks from 88 countries and regions. Its forerunner was the
International Saving Banks Association set up in Milan, Italy, in
1924.
</P>
<P>
There are 14 members from 11 countries and regions on WSBI
Asian-Pacific regional group. Chinese members of the Asian-Pacific
group are the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC),
Postal Saving and Remittance Bureau of China, and Caixa Economica
Postal de Macau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
