<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Promote Cultural Prosperity: Outlook Weekly (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China's Minister of Culture Sun
Jiazheng said that the state is determined to raise the overall
quality of cultural products and improve management of the
cultural industry in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Sun said in the latest issue of Outlook Weekly which hit
newsstands today China plans to speed up the construction of
symbolic cultural buildings, such as a proposed national museum, a
giant national theater and other high-level museums in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
Sun said that his ministry also wants to encourage cultural
advancement in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state wants funding for the cultural industry,
including money for publications and entertainment, according to
the magazine.
</P>
<P>
All performing groups and localities are urged to raise their
performance quality in the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to make art groups financially self-sufficient, the
ministry will deepen reforms inside the groups, especially those
with outstanding artists.
</P>
<P>
The performing groups will be regarded as businesses and should
make their own ends meet while increasing their competitiveness,
the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Global economic integration and China's entry into the World
Trade Organization will create both challenges and opportunities
for the Chinese people, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Promote Cultural Prosperity: Outlook Weekly (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese nation has outstanding cultural traditions which
reflect unique national characteristics, Sun said. The ministry
aims to preserve the country's abundant heritage, including both
cultural ruins and folk arts.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a comprehensive, long-term project for relics
protection and tourist development is needed, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
Sun urged localities to safeguard treasured relics and
supervise archaeological excavations.
</P>
<P>
The ministry wants to complete the main structure of cultural
laws and regulations completed by the end of 2015, the magazine
said.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the ministry, anyone found guilty of
publishing piracy may face more severe punishment in the future.
</P>
<P>
Sun underscored the importance of the anti-piracy campaign in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also vows to strike hard against prostitution at
nightclubs and other places of entertainment, the magazine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
