<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Leaves for Summit with Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak is heading to Washington Monday afternoon on a mission to
inject more vitality into the faltering Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Barak is due to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington
on Tuesday to try to rescue the stalled peace talks with the
Syrians and push ahead the final-status talks with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He will also discuss with Clinton about Israel's planned troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon by July this year.
</P>
<P>
En route, Barak is set to hold talks in Cairo with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak, whose Foreign minister Amr Moussa said on
Sunday that Israel's peace talks with the Palestinians are in a
serious crisis.
</P>
<P>
Before the departure, Barak, who had expressed his deep
pessimism about the chances of renewing peace talks with the
Syrians, laid out his vision of solving the key issues in the
final-status talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He said on Sunday that Israel will not give the sovereignty to
the Palestinians over big Jewish settlements in the West Bank, but
will transfer all Palestinian villages outside Jerusalem, including
Abu Dis and Anata, to the Palestinians in the future Israeli troop
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
He also said the most areas in the West Bank designated as Area
B, which are under Palestinian civil control and Israeli security
control, will, under a permanent-status agreement, be transferred
to full Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
He added the Palestinian entity should be as continuous as
possible, so that Palestinians should not have to go through
roadblocks to get from one part to another and their leaders should
not need permission to leave its borders.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the Palestinian refugees, Barak said that Israel will
take neither legal nor moral responsibility for the refugees and
the solution to this problem is not within Israel.
</P>
<P>
Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, commenting on the
upcoming Washington summit, said Monday it is time for Israel and
the Palestinians to "put their cards on the table" ahead of a May
deadline to draw up a framework deal for a final peace agreement
which must solve the toughest issues such as the fate of Jerusalem
and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks were stalled in January after the
two sides held two rounds of talks in the United States since last
December, due to Israel's refusal to promise to return to Syria all
the Golan Heights it occupied during the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
