<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Launch Fresh Attack on Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan government troops
Monday launched a fresh offensive against Tamil rebels in the
northern Jaffna Peninsula to recapture a stretch of a vital
highway, according to military spokesman B.P. Fernando.
</P>
<P>
The troops had moved out on one front south of Pallai, which
has seen fighting in the past two weeks since the rebels launched
a push for the strategic Elephant Pass military base linking the
mainland and the Jaffna Peninsula, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting broke out between Sri Lankan government troops
on a highway between Eluthumadduval and Muhamaalai Monday morning
as the troops made yet another attempt to recapture more than six
kilometers of the road to the Elephant Pass, reports reaching here
from the north of the country said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have pounded each other with artillery and
mortars while the Sri Lankan Air Force has bombed several rebel
targets as the rebels have resisted the military's advance.
</P>
<P>
The fighting is fierce but details of casualties on both sides
were still not available, the reports added.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels who have been fighting a war against the
government since 1983 for a separate state in the country,
launched a major offensive two weeks ago to take the Elephant Pass,
a vital road bridge, in a bid to recapture the Jaffna Peninsula
which they lost to government troops in May 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
