<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Demands Total Ban on Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Sun Huixia
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
 reiterated Kenya's stand on the total ban on ivory trade here
Monday, saying that the poaching of elephants has increased due to
some southern African countries' one-off sales of ivory to Japan
approved by CITES in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"We in Kenya see evidence that the illegal killing of elephants
has increased while no reliable monitoring system has been put in
place," Moi said at the opening ceremony of the 11th conference of
Parties to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
"I am pointing this out because one tends to forget that
actions in one country can significantly affect the situation in
others," Moi added.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that the system of Monitoring the iIlegal Killing of
Elephants, which was proposed to set up in 1997, is not truly
representative of CITES membership.
</P>
<P>
The president also noted that the problem of poaching has
adversely affected Kenya's tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
Botswana, Zimbabwe, Namibia and South africa, have proposed to
be authorized by CITES to have an annual quota for further sales.
</P>
<P>
Kenya and India have demanded a return to the full ban on the
ivory trade, citing the southern African sale stimulated poaching
greatly and that CITES member countries had failed to curb the
illegal ivory trade.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which ends on April 20, is expected to review
62 proposals to amend the trade controls or bans on international
trade in endangered species. The ivory issue has been the focus of
the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
