<HEADLINE> Pine Worms Detected in Wood Packing for Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers in east China's
Jiangsu Province have reported the appearance of harmful pine
worms in the wood packing of three batches of imported goods from
Japan and two batches of imported goods from the United States,
according to the Beijing-based International Business Daily
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The worm, mainly found in the U.S., Japan and Canada, is so
dangerous to pine trees that it is known as "pine cancer."
</P>
<P>
To protect forests and the country's eco-environment, China in
January launched special quarantine measures for the wood packing
used in imports from Japan and the U.S., stipulating that all
shipments using wood packing should be accompanied by heat
treatment certificates.  
</P>
