<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's TB Control Needs Governmental Commitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has been
urged to increase funding for its anti-tuberculosis (TB) campaign
to avoid further spread of the infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
"About half of the country's TB patients have no access to
treatment or are forced to halt the treatment due to poverty, even
though the illness is curable with drugs," said Professor Duanmu
Hongjin, director of the National Tuberculosis Control Center.
</P>
<P>
China currently has six million TB patients, the world's second
largest total next to India. About 250,000 of China's TB sufferers
die each year.
</P>
<P>
If no preventive measures are taken, more than 200 million
healthy Chinese may be infected with tubercle bacillus, the
bacteria that leads to TB, in the next decade, and one tenth of
them may become full-fledged TB patients, Chinese doctors have
warned.
</P>
<P>
Although an effective treatment, called "directly observed
treatment, short course" (DOTS), has been available in China for
many years, the majority of poor farmers cannt afford the service
which costs 200 to 300 yuan (24 to 36 U.S. dollars) per period of
treatment, said Prof. Duanmu.
</P>
<P>
The prevalence of TB in China's rural areas 2.4 times that in
cities.
</P>
<P>
"What is most needed now is the commitment of governments at
all levels," he said, indicating that more funding should be
allocated since a TB-control project will be completed next year.
The project, aided by the World Bank, will cover almost half of
the Chinese population and provide free treatment.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the ministries of health and finance said a
special national TB fund will be established.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Duanmu also heads the Beijing Tuberculosis and Thoracic
Tumor Research Institute, China's first TB control agency, founded
in 1955.
</P>
<P>
As the domestic leader of TB research and treatment, the
institute has initiated a series of advanced therapies while
developing new drugs, according to Duanmu.
</P>
<P>
The institute also is involved in the research of lung cancer,
which threatens many Chinese. More than 6,000 lung cancer patients
have undergone surgery, and their five-year survival rate has
reached 35 percent, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
