<HEADLINE> Iranian Opposition Group Headquarters in Iraq Shelled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The headquarters of the Iranian
opposition group Mujahidin Khalq in southern Iraq were shelled
Sunday by mercenaries infiltrating into Iraq from "a neighboring
country," announced an Iraqi official on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Iraqi News Agency (INA), the official said
that a number of mercenaries fired mortar shells at the
headquarters of the Iraq-based Iranian opposition organization.
</P>
<P>
No casualties were reported, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The attackers have fled back to their bases in the "neighboring
country," said the official, asking not to be named.
</P>
<P>
Iraq vehemently condemns these terrorist acts as well as those
who stand behind them, stressing that Iraq has full rights to
defend its interior security and seize the terrorists wherever they
go, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Mujahidin Khalq has been a major Iraq-based armed group
conducting activities against the Iranian government ever since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
For years, Iraq and Iran, the two Gulf neighbors who fought a
bloody war from 1980 to 1988, have been trading accusations against
each other for harboring each other's opposition groups engaged in
terrorist activities, hampering the normalization of bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has claimed that on March 22, four Iraqi civilians were
killed and 38 others injured in a mortar attack by Iranian agents
against densely-populated residential areas in the capital Baghdad.
</P>
</TEXT>
