<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldier to be Extradited to Canada for Murder Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Jerusalem District Court Judge
Zvi Cohen ruled on Monday that Daniel Weiz, a 19-year-old soldier
of Israel Defense Forces, is eligible to be extradited to Canada to
face a second-degree murder charge.
</P>
<P>
Weiz is suspected by Toronto police of taking part in the brutal
beating to death of a teenage Canadian in a Toronto park last
November, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Weiz denied all the charges. His lawyer Nitzana Darshan-Leitner
had announced that her client will appeal the ruling to Israel's
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
According to the police's accusations, Weiz, who lives in Israel
with his mother and has duel Israeli-Canadian citizenship, was
involved in the case while he was on a three-month furlough in
Toronto with his father.
</P>
<P>
On November 14, 1999, a dozen of youths ambushed Dmitri
Baranovsky, a 15-year-old Canadian boy, and his friends in a
Toronto park, demanding money and cigarettes. Four of the gang
allegedly beat and kicked Baranovsky to death.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian police had kept several suspects in custody on
charges of second-degree murder. In the interrogation of them, Weiz
was identified as one of the murderers.
</P>
<P>
As Weiz had returned to Israel and rejoined his army service at
that time, Canada asked Israeli Justice Ministry to extradite him
to stand trial for the case. He was then arrested at his army base
last December.
</P>
<P>
Weiz's lawyer argued that Toronto should hand over all testimony
gathered in the case to Israeli authorities before the court could
decide on the demand of extradition.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer said Toronto police have deliberately withheld some
affidavits, in which some other suspects are identified as the
killers, including the two who blamed Weiz. Thus, she asserted, her
client was framed.
</P>
<P>
However, State Attorney Irit Kohn said the state does not have
to prove that Weiz is guilty, but only that there is enough
suspicions to warrant the extradition.
</P>
<P>
According to the recently revised extradition law in Israel,
Israeli citizens could be handed over to stand trial in other
countries on condition that they, if found guilty, will serve
sentences in Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
