<HEADLINE> Nigerian Ex-Presidents to be Summoned for Poor Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's former heads of state,
including Gen Ibrahim Babangida, Chief Ernest Shonekan, Gen
Abdulsalami Abubakar, and former Central Bank governors may soon
be summoned by the Senate over the poor state of the nation's
accounts.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper on Monday quoted the chairman of Senate
 Committee on Public Accounts, Alhaji Abubakar, as disclosing on
Sunday that the federal government's accounts were "in tatters",
and as a result, billions of naira could not be accounted for.
</P>
<P>
He told The Guardian that the invitation to the former leaders
became imperative because of the huge sums of money involved.
</P>
<P>
He expressed shock at the committee's discovery that accounts
of the various ministries and parastatals had not been audited for
about six years.
</P>
<P>
The poor handling of the accounting system resulted in
increased wastage and embezzlement, particularly between 1992 and
May 29, 1999 when president Olusegun Obasanjo took over, ending
15-year military rule.  
</P>
</TEXT>
