<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D.R. Congo, Its Allies Urge U.N. to Deploy Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of Congo (D.
R. Congo) and its allies have appealed to the United Nations to
deploy as soon as possible truce observers to avoid the outbreak
of another large-scale war in the region.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made at a mini-summit held on Sunday at the
headquarters of the Organization of African Unity in the D.R.
Congo's capital of Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Radio Voix du People, the official radio
station of the D.R. Congo, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who
was attending the summit, said that the leaders present hope that
the United Nations will deploy the group of truce observers
immediately.
</P>
<P>
"This is very important, because there is a danger that the
situation will deteriorate. The war risks to resume on a big scale,
" said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Also at the summit were D.R. Congo President Laurent Desire
Kabila, Angolan President Jose Edouardo Dos Santos and Namibian
President Sam Nujoma.
</P>
<P>
The leaders discussed the military and political situation in
the D.R. Congo since a truce agreement was signed in Lusaka in
last July to end the war, which broke out in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
A truce agreement was signed last Saturday in Kampala, Uganda,
between the D.R. Congo government, the rebels and their ally
countries -- Uganda and Rwanda, who decided to cease all actions
of hostility from the mid-night of April 14.
</P>
<P>
The Kampala agreement is seen as aiming apparently at creating
favorable conditions for the deployment of the U.N. mission of
observers.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has agreed to send observers and a 5,000-
strong peacekeeping force to the D.R. Congo to supervise the truce
and the withdrawal of all foreign forces from the country.
</P>
<P>
But the U.N. has so far delayed the deployment because of lack
of security guarantees for its personnel from the belligerent
sides.
</P>
<P>
The D.R. Congo government forces and the rebels are still
confronting each other on the eastern and northwest borders of the
D.R. Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
