<P>
SANAA -- Preliminary data showed that trade balance registered a
surplus amounting to 67.2 billion Yemeni rials (417 million U.S.
dollars) at the end of 1999 as compared to about 112.4 billion
rials (698 million dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Arab daily Al Hayat on Monday published the figures issued
by the Yemeni Central Agency for Statistics as saying the total
value of imports reached 212.7 billion (1.9 billion dollars), while
the value of exports were estimated at some 380 billion rials (2.3
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Mouaz Barakat, the World Gold Council's regional
manager of the Middle East, said Saudi Arabia's production of gold
is estimated at about six tons annually, and its annual consumption
is put at some 200 tons while its sales reached some 3 billion
rials (800 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Al Hayat on Monday quoted Barakat as saying the volume of gold
consumption in the Gulf region is estimated at around 350 tons
every year, and some 700 tons in the Arab world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's outstanding external debt reached 111.2
billion dollars at the end of 1999, a 7.08 percent increase from
the previous year, reported Turkish Daily News on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury said over the weekend that at the end of 1998,
outstanding external debt totalled 103.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's short-term external debt was up 7.6 percent from the
end of 1998, accounting for 26.34 percent of the total external
debt stock, the Treasury said.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) will grant Jordan 200
million dollars in the year 2000 to support its economy and promote
development projects, the semi-official Jordan Times reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan has asked the
government to make the transfer as soon as possible to help Jordan
in its projects to attract foreign investments and reduce
unemployment rates, which officially stands at over 14 percent as
against 27 percent by independent estimates.
</P>
<P>
The UAE also transferred 100 million dollars in February 1999 to
the Central Bank of Jordan to help stabilize its currency and to
help the economic situation of the kingdom, which was suffering
from a record 7.9 billion dollars of foreign debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
