<HEADLINE> Philippines to Bring in Low-Priced Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
finalizing negotiations with foreign drug manufacturers to bring
in low-priced quality medicines into the country as part of its
efforts to make life-saving health care available to the poor.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Mar Roxas of the Department of Trade and Industry
said Monday that the government is now in the process of coming up
with a list of widely used brands of drugs which are priced too
high for Filipino consumers so that these could be placed in the
priority list of medicines that would be imported at low prices.
</P>
<P>
"These are the steps that we are doing right now. In my view,
after several months we can actually pass on these low-priced
medicines to consumers," he said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Roxas said medicine manufacturers in India were the first to
discuss the possibility of bringing in low-priced medicines into
the country.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada, who has mobilized the
government machinery to tap ways of pulling down medicine prices,
has noted earlier that medicines in India cost 10 times less than
those sold in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Roxas said that aside from accelerating the process
of bringing in these low-priced medicines into the country, the
government is also making sure that quality control is strictly
observed in the importation of these goods.
</P>
<P>
"The first ones to talk with us were Indian drug companies.
What is important here is not just bringing in these low-priced
medicines, but also taking into account quality control," he said.
</P>
<P>
Roxas said the government is taking this initiative to place"
competitive pressure" on other medicine manufacturers which hold a
virtual monopoly on the retailing and distribution of medicines in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
