<HEADLINE> Zanzibar's Population to Double to 1.6m in 2008 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar's population would
double from 800,000 to reach more than 1.6 million by 2008, a
senior official of the Zanzibar Revolution Government has said.
</P>
<P>
The Principal Secretary in the Ministry of State (Planning and
Investments) Omar Yussuf Mzee warned that the rapid population
growth would worsen unemployment, land scarcity, housing shortage
and environmental destruction.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the draft version of the population policy, Yussuf
told a special committee of the Zanzibar House of Representatives
that the island' s rapid annual population growth of three percent
must be checked.
</P>
<P>
The legislators said that there should be a specific version of
the National population policy to deal with Zanzibar's special
problems from the grassroots to the national levels as well as
their solutions.
</P>
<P>
They argued that such a document would define priorities and
strategies on the population boom which had adverse effect on the
delivery of social services and employment.
</P>
<P>
For example, they pointed out that over 52 percent of
Zanzibar's 800, 000 population are non-productive and there are
great inequalities of life between men and women especially in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The representatives also called for strict measures to check
immigration into the island, saying the government's annual budget
especially in provision of social services is often
over-stretched.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar, consisted of the main Unguja island and its sister
island of Pemba with a total area of 2,642 square kilometers in
the western part of the Indian Ocean, lies some 40 kilometers east
of the mainland of Tanzania whose population stands at about 30
million at present.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar and the then Republic of Tanganyika merged in 1964 to
form the United Republic of Tanzania, but it has its own
government dealing with affairs except foreign and defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
