<HEADLINE> WTO to Fund Developing Countries' Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization (WTO)
has set aside a special technical assistance fund to boost the
agriculture sector of developing countries across the world,
Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the fund can be accessed by any
country that puts up a program to the international trade
organization regarding its needs.
</P>
<P>
It quoted an economist from the United States, Daniel Plunkett,
as saying in an interview with the newspaper at the weekend that
all developing countries who fall under the category of Net Food
Importers can access special permission for funds, infrastructure
and technology.
</P>
<P>
Plunkett, who is a member of the Associates for International
Resources and Development Economists Team, called on African
countries to take advantage of the funds.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed the development after the close of the workshop on
the WTO and agriculture organization by the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) and by the United States
International Development (USAID).
</P>
<P>
WTO has been accused by developing countries of spearheading
the interests of developed countries at the expense of least
developed countries. 
</P>
