<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Explains His Role in Zimbabwe-Britain Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- President Olusegun Obasanjo Sunday
in London shed light on his role in the face-off between Britain
and Zimbabwe, saying he merely acted as a "midwife" rather than
as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper Monday quoted
Obasanjo as expressing confidence that the row between the two
countries would be resolved amicably.
</P>
<P>
"I acted as a midwife and got Robin Cook, British Foreign
Secretary and Robert Mugabe, Zimbabwean President, together to
discuss problems between their countries," he said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said that when he brought the two countries to a
dialogue, " I was told not to go away, I sat down as an impartial
listener."
</P>
<P>
On his trip to Cuba, Obasanjo said the G-77 meeting would
discuss important issues such as North-South and South-South
co-operation, globalization and its implication on development,
trade and monetary affairs.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that a roll-back malaria meeting would be
held in Abuja later in the month to discuss ways of reducing the
scourge in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, sponsored by Nigeria, World Health Organization,
some African countries and international organizations, is aimed
at curtailing the high mortality rate resulting from this
disease.
</P>
<P>
The President told the audience during his stopover visit to
the United Kingdom on his way to Cuba that his administration has
succeeded in restoring hope among Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Many Nigerians, according to him, now believe that government's
economic and other programs would take the country out of its
economic doldrums.
</P>
<P>
He explained that hope was an essential part of life without
which existence may be meaningless. 
</P>
