<HEADLINE> Portuguese Descent Kidnapped by Angolan Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- An Angolan coffee planter of
Portuguese descent was kidnapped by the Angolan rebels in a recent
attack on the town of Calulo, a relative said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Henrique Chaves Fonseca, 64, and an undetermined number of
other residents were seized by the rebels and forced to serve as
porters for goods sacked by the rebels when their forces withdrew
from Calulo, a strategic town located in the central Kwanza-sul
province, some 230 kilometers southeast to the Angolan capital
Luanda.
</P>
<P>
Since late March, Calulo has been disturbed by the rebels of
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA),
who occupied the town on March 31 but soon repelled by the
government troops after a counter-offensive, said local analysts.
</P>
<P>
Fonseca, the Angola-born son of Portuguese parents, had been
the target of a previous UNITA attack, when his Kwanza-sul coffee
plantation was raided by the rebels, according to the relative.
</P>
<P>
After the UNITA occupation of Calulo and heavy fighting in a
surprise operation on March 31, thousands of people fled the
region as government forces mounted a successful
counter-offensive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
