<HEADLINE> Guinea-Bissau Appoints Civilian as Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Guinea-Bissau President Kumba Iala
has appointed a civilian as the country's new defense minister,
with an aim to promote the process of returning the country back
to full civilian rule, local radio station said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Iala named Fernando Correia, an engineer, to the post of
defense minister, to replace Lt. Col. Verissimo Correia Seabra,
who was the chief of staff of the armed forces and now returned to
his original position.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Col. Seabra, who joined the government on February 19, had
recently ceased going to his ministry or attending cabinet
meetings.
</P>
<P>
The move was considered by local analysts as the reflection of
the military's desire for a full return to barracks after its
1998-99 rebellion that deposed President Nino Vieira, after which
the multi party elections were realized in the western African
country.
</P>
<P>
The insurrection's leader, Brigadier Ansumane Mane, has
promised that with the return to constitutional rule, following
presidential and legislative balloting at the turn of the year,
the military would fully withdraw from political life. 
