<HEADLINE> China Independently Develops Satellite Perigee Solid Kick Motor: Statement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China has developed the satellite
perigee kick motor, known as EPKM, entirely relying on its own
efforts, according to a spokesman of China Great Wall Industry
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made such a statement on the media reported
charge to Lockheed Martin by the U.S. State Department regarding
the alleged technical assistance of launch vehicle technology to
China.
</P>
<P>
"We have noticed that according to U.S. media reports, the U.S.
Department stated that China has probably acquired technical
assistance from Lockheed Martin in 1994 in the development of the
EPKM," the spokesman said, pointing out that "This is groundless
and irresponsible."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Independently Develops Satellite Perigee Solid Kick Motor: Statement (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the spokesman, on March 2, 1993, the China Great
Wall Industry Corporation and Asia Satellite Telecommunications Co.
Ltd. signed a launch services contract by using LM-2E launch
vehicle to launch the Lockheed Martin built AsiaSat-2 satellite
into low earth orbit and a purchase agreement for a perigee kick
motor.
</P>
<P>
The selection of LM-2E launch vehicle to launch AsiaSat-2 by
Asia Satellite Telecommunications Co. Ltd. was based on the fact
that China's space industry has had 40-year's experience in
successfully developing multiple versions of launch vehicles, and
has mastered mature technology on both liquid and solid motors and
manufactured a variety of solid motors of the similar
specifications, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hereby responsibly state that China has developed the
satellite perigee kick motor entirely relying on its own efforts.
We have never acquired from Lockheed Martin or other party any
technical assistance in this regard," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
