<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ to Discontinue Knight, Damehoods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 10 4 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Helen Clark announced here Monday that her government has decided
to discontinue in future the titles of Sir and Dame in the country
's honors system.
</P>
<P>
In a government statement, the prime minister noted that Knight
and Damehoods overshadow not only New Zealand's highest honor, the
Order of New Zealand, but also a large number of other awards
given for an extraordinary variety of services to a wide cross-
section of the community.
</P>
<P>
Noting that New Zealand has its own honors system, Clark said
discontinuing the use of British awards will complete the work in
replacing a mixed honors system with a wholly New Zealand one.
</P>
<P>
The decision to discontinue Knight and Damehoods will be put
into effect before the Queen's Birthday honors to be announced on
June 5th, the prime minister said, adding that these changes will
be applied to future recipients only and all current knights and
dames will retain their existing titles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
