<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Common Efforts Lead to Inter-Korean Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
will travel to Pyongyang in June for a historic summit with Kim
Jong Il, top leader of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (
DPRK), the first-ever between the two sides since the Korean War
in the early 1950s, both Seoul and Pyongyang announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The long-delayed summit, which is widely expected to be a
turning point in the inter-Korean ties, was a result of common
efforts made in recent years by the two sides to promote
reconciliation and peace on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK and South Korea had agreed to hold a summit in July
1994 between the then DPRK President Kim Il Sung and his South
Korean counterpart Kim Young-sam. But the scheduled meeting was
canceled due to the sudden death of Kim Il Sung.
</P>
<P>
After six years, the two sides reached the agreement to resume
the summit during a meeting in Beijing last Saturday between South
Korean Culture and Tourism Minister Park Jie-won and Song Ho Gyong,
vice chairman of the DPRK's Asia-Pacific Peace Committee.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the announcement of the news, Kim Dae-jung said the
summit may serve as an opportunity for national prosperity and
development and bring hope for the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Since President Kim Dae-jung was inaugurated in February 1998,
South Korea has provided food, fertilizers and other humanitarian
assistance to the DPRK, which has been in economic trouble because
of natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
On March 9 this year, Kim Dae-jung proposed in Berlin, Germany,
that South Korea give more economic aid to the DPRK based on inter-
Korean direct dialogue.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the DPRK has made untiring efforts to promote
dialogue between the governments of the two sides and between the
two peoples, and continued contact with the South Korean
government during recent years.
</P>
<P>
In February 1999, the DPRK government, in an open letter to the
South Korean authorities and all political parties in the country,
proposed that the year 1999 be set as a year for enhancing
national reconciliation and unity. It also proposed wide-ranging
dialogue between the two sides including that between the two
governments.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held two vice ministerial meetings in Beijing in
April 1998 and in June 1999 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming summit, the first of its kind since the
governments of the two sides were established in 1948, will give
the two leaders a historic chance to discuss matters on the cause
of peaceful coexistence on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
They are believed to focus their talks on economic cooperation,
humanitarian assistance, reunion of separated families, stability
and peace on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The summit, if realized, will surely pave the way for South
Korea to help the DPRK build electric power system, roads and
other infrastructure, and impose a positive impact on negotiations
on improving ties between the DPRK and the United States and other
western states.
</P>
<P>
However, some analysts said the summit will not produce results
easily due to the deeply-rooted mutual distrust even though the
strong political will of the two leaders will likely allow the
summit to go ahead as scheduled under widespread international
expectations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Marathon Favourite Withdraws  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Runner Jon Brown, one of the
favourites for this weekend's London Marathon, has had to pull out
due to injury.
</P>
<P>
The British number one, who eyes the Olympic games as his
priority, said he had withdrawn from the marathon as a
precautionary measure.
</P>
<P>
Brown, who has been carrying a hip injury since winning a
bronze medal when leading Great Britain to team victory for the
first time in last December's European Cross Country Championships,
plans to return to full-time training in a few weeks' time.
</P>
<P>
He was fourth in last year's London Marathon with a personal
best time of two hours nine minutes and 44 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The Sheffield star has been receiving intensive treatment from
UK Athletics physiotherapist Neil Black.
</P>
<P>
But on Saturday the 29-year-old realised he had lost his race
against the clock. He said: "After having treatment the injury is
not so serious. But if I was to run I would want to be at my most
competitive. At the moment I am not - so my London plans will have
to wait for another year."
</P>
<P>
Brown missed the recent World Cross Country Championships to
concentrate totally on the London Marathon.
</P>
<P>
He added: "Of course I'm disappointed at missing the race after
all the preparations I have put in. But with the injury there
would always have been a risk factor - one I wasn't prepared to
take."
</P>
<P>
Already pre-selected for September's Sydney Games, the British
10,000m record holder added: "The Olympic Games are more important
than anything else this year. I do not plan to run another
marathon beforehand but now intend to do a few track races to
maintain my racing edge."
</P>
<P>
Brown, who has been based in Vancouver for the past couple of
years, arrived in London three weeks ago hoping treatment from
Black would give him a quick cure.
</P>
<P>
Now he intends returning to Canada as soon as his physiotherapy
treatment is concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
