<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Rules out Disarming Palestinian Refugees in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has
ruled out disarming Palestinian refugees in Lebanon as part of an
Israeli withdrawal from the south of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian presence in Lebanon is wholly legitimate
according to principles laid down at the Arab summit in Cairo in
1970," Arafat told Egyptian reporters on Sunday after meeting with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was "indignant" at the suggestion that Palestinian
refugees in Lebanon might be disarmed, Egypt's Al-ahram daily
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Emile Lahoud filed a memorandum last week
with the United Nations, asking if a multi-national force would be
willing to disarm Palestinian refugees as part of an agreement on
an Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has pledged a unilateral withdrawal from southern Lebanon
it has occupied for 22 years, even in the absence of a peace accord
with Syria, which exerts key influence on Lebanon with some 35,000
troops there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
