<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- On the eve of his departure for the United States for a
summit with U.S. President Bill Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak Sunday laid out his vision of a future Palestinian
entity.
</P>
<P>
He said that while some Jewish settlements near Jerusalem will
be part of a united Jerusalem in the future, there is "no interest"
in annexing the approximately 50,000 Palestinians living in
villages on the capital's outskirts, such as Abu Dis and Anata.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the cabinet Sunday that most areas designated as Area
B - under Palestinian civil control and Israeli security control -
will, under a permanent-status agreement, be transferred to full
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- A decision by Israel's High Court which enables an Arab
family to buy a house in a Jewish settlement has prompted the
government to consider dramatic expansion of housing opportunities
in Arab villages, and for the first time in the state's history,
the establishment of a new town for Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Except for some towns established for Bedouin in the Negev, no
new Arab cities have been established in Israel since its founding.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Syria has toughened its position in its official reply to
proposals made by U.S. President Clinton in his March 26 meeting
with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, according to well-informed
sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Syria is demanding a total Israeli withdrawal
from the Golan Heights to the lines of June 4, 1967, Syrian
sovereignty on the shore of the Kinneret, and the right to part of
the lake.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Damascus is adamantly opposed to an early-warning
station on Mount Hermon after a withdrawal, and will begin
normalization with Israel only after the evacuation of the Golan is
completed.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas Sunday fired a mortar shell
that struck Moshav Margaliot on the Lebanese border, damaging the
community's chicken coops but hurting nobody.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Defense Forces suggested that the targeting of
Margaliot was not an accident but was intended to intensify the
internal debate within Israel over the withdrawal from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The IDF says the past two weeks have seen a 20 percent leap in
the scale of fighting in south Lebanon, a sign that Hezbollah wants
to show the world that it is the guerrillas that force Israeli
soldiers out of Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
