<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Development Should Be Culture-Based: TRF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Industrial development in
Thailand should be based on the country's precious cultures, a
report released by the Thailand Research Fund (TRF) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the industrial sector has played an
increasing role in Thailand's modern development since the country
launched its First National Economic and Social Development Plan
in 1961, with its contribution to the economic growth rising to 33.
7 percent of the gross domestic products (GDP) in 1998, from 15.8
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, it argued that due to rapidly-changing situations of
globalization, Thailand's industrial development could not rely
only on capital and technology-intensive industries under the
trade liberalization framework, in which developed nations have
always had comparative advantages over developing countries, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The industries should be based on the strength of traditional
Thai cultures, arts, and people's wisdom, proficiency and
lifestyles, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The unique Thai cultural assets should be transformed into the
production of Thai-branded products, namely, various types and
styles of handicrafts, and gem and jewelry, as well as the
development of Thai tourism and related industries, reflecting the
recognized Thai characteristics of generosity and artistic talents,
it suggested.
</P>
<P>
These industries were seen to be able to compete with developed
countries and could bring in substantial revenues to the country,
it stated.
</P>
<P>
But the report said that modern technologies were needed to the
development of the industries to help upgrade production processes
and quality of the culture-based products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
