<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Open Up Local Law Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will soon open up its
local law firms so as to provide them an opportunity to join the
ranks of international firms to become global legal service
providers, Singapore Chief Justice Yong Pung How told a law
conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Legal Profession (Amendment) was before Parliament. It allows
joint ventures and formal alliances between Singapore and offshore
law firms and the corporatization of law firms," the chief justice
said when addressing the opening of the Singapore Law Conference
under the theme "Leading the Law and Lawyers into the New
Millennium."
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference organized by the Singapore Academy of
Law is attended by some 500 participants including over 80 foreign
delegates from 19 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
"Such joint ventures between onshore and offshore firms will
enable the former to gain considerably in terms of knowledge and
skill, and in the development of legal databases, technology and
management know-how," Yong said
</P>
<P>
"We must be able to offer something more to entice foreigners
to use our legal system and our lawyers," he added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that new laws are continually promulgated and current
legislation revisited and revamped in order to keep abreast of
modern developments and to ensure that they meet with
international standards, Yong underlined that this is especially
pertinent given the explosion of developments and issues in
intellectual property, information technology, e-commerce and
trans-border commercial crimes.
</P>
<P>
Referring to initiatives adopted within Singapore's judiciary
to meet the new challenges, Yong cited the speed-up of the trial
process and quick disposal of cases which allows a civil suit now
be heard in a mere six months from the date of commencement of the
action and the reorganization of sources which can offer more
diversified services such as night courts and court dispute
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The court dispute resolution, introduced by the Subordinate
Courts last year as the Court Dispute Resolution-International
Regime, is a form of co-mediation conducted by local judicial
officers together with judges from other common law jurisdictions
through settlement conference using video conferencing facilities.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's legal system belongs to the English common law
family. The judicial power in Singapore is vested in the Supreme
Court and in the Subordinate Courts and an Attorney-General is
appointed by the President on advice of the Prime Minister to act
as the principal legal adviser to the government. The ministry of
law has the mission to ensure legal infrastructure and to optimize
the allocation of the nation's land resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
