<HEADLINE> Malaysia Invited to Invest in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 10 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Monday invited
Malaysian investors to tap the vast opportunities available in the
country in the area of manufacturing, electronics,
telecommunications and marine industries.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was extended by John Maasland, chairman of ASEAN-
New Zealand Combined Business Council who said that New Zealand
has made several changes after the economic crisis and it
currently offered a very open business environment.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand practices a free market economy and allows freedom
of capital investment on trade, he said at a lunch talk hosted by
New Zealand High Commissioner Sarrah Dennis here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia ranked the 11th under New Zealand's trade profile with
its exports to New Zealand amounting to 261.4 million U.S.dollars
while its imports stood at 208.4 million U.S. dollars for the last
financial year ending June 1999.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's exports to New Zealand consisted, among others,
crude oil, automatic data processing machines, television
receivers, radio-telephony, furniture, palm oil, soya-bean oil,
fertilizers and electronic integrated circuits and microassemblies
as well as natural rubber.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's main items of imports from New Zealand included milk
powder, frozen beef, butter and wood pulp as well as sheep or goat
meat, buttermilk, fish, cheese and curd and fresh fruits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
