<HEADLINE> Asia Software Policy Summit Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 10 (Xinhua) -- A meeting on software policy
opened here Monday with the aim of identifying positive government
policies and practices to expand the overall size of the software
industry and increase Asia-Pacific participation in that growth.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Asia Software Policy Summit, the first ever of its
kind in the region, will address software asset management,
intellectual property protection, the role of a strong and vibrant
software industry and e-commerce policies impacting the industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the summit's organizers, in Asia alone, the
software industry lost about 3 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 to
piracy which also directly impacted on tax revenues and employment
rates.
</P>
<P>
Participants from Malaysia, Indonesia, Philippines, Thailand,
India, Hong Kong, Hungary, Italy, Belgium and the United States to
the summit are to jointly formulate an action agenda to reduce
piracy in the region, the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The summit is hosted by Malaysia's Domestic Trade and Consumer
Affairs Ministry and the Business Software Alliance with the
cooperation of Malaysia's Multimedia Development Corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
