<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police to Quell Political Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean police have taken new
measures to quell political violence that has so far claimed three
lives and left about 100 people injured since January this year,
The Herald newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police Spokesman Chief Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena said on
Sunday that police had introduced patrols in most areas ahead of
parliamentary elections scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
The police is mounting roadblocks in search of weapons that
might be used in political violence.
</P>
<P>
He said although the force would spare no effort in dealing
with political violence, it still had its limitations.
</P>
<P>
"It still remains the responsibility of the political
leadership to encourage their supporters to carry out their
activities in a peaceful manner," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the police's role would mainly be reactive due to
 limitations in anticipating the outbreaks of violence.
</P>
<P>
However, the force was fully prepared and equipped to deal with
any eventualities arising from political violence, he said.
</P>
<P>
Election campaigns have so far been characterized by violent
clashes, mainly between the ruling Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front and the opposition Movement for Democratic
Change supporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
