<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Boost Tea Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will increase green tea
leaf production from current 640,000 tons to one million tons
annually within next five years, the Kenya Tea Development
Authority has said.
</P>
<P>
General Manager Richard Cheruiyot made the announcement over
the weekend, saying his authority will change to a marketing
agency by July 1, the East African Standard newspaper said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cheruiyot said the restructuring of the authority and
liberalization of the tea sector before his agency is eventually
put under privatization is tailored to benefit the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Just two days ago, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi said his
government had de-linked itself from the tea sector, leaving the
sector to farmers to manage their own affairs and have the
controlling voice in the management of the industry.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is one of the world's largest black tea suppliers and
last year it exported more than 241,000 tons of tea, accounting
for about a quarter of the country's foreign exchange earnings.
The tea sector employs over two million people across the country.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
