<HEADLINE> Zambia to Seek Release of 30 Abducted Villagers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government has started
negotiations with the concerned authorities of the Democratic
Republic of the Congo to seek the release of 30 villagers abducted
from Northwestern province by suspected Congolese armed people
last week.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail on Monday quoted Provincial Permanent
Secretary Maybin Mubanga as saying that a team of Zambian military
personnel has been sent to Mwinilunga of the province to join the
district administrator to have negotiations with the Congolese
side over the release of the villagers.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation in the province and Mwinilunga in
particular is under control.
</P>
<P>
The 30 villagers were reportedly abducted by the armed
Congolese, who later demanded 80,000 kwacha (less than 30 U.S.
dollars) for the release of each hostage.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the villagers have been found harvesting
crops in Congolese villagers' fields across the border. 
