<HEADLINE> Dar Listed as the Most Costly City for Business in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Dar es Salaam is said to be
the most costly city for business people in East Africa due to
high charges levied by the City Commission, the African newspaper
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey recently conducted by a committee jointly
formed by the Dar es Salaam Regional Chapter of the Tanzania
Chamber of Commerce, Industry and Agriculture (TCCIA) and the Dar
es Salaam Merchants' Chamber, Dar es Salaam is found to be the
most costly city for doing business in comparison with the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which was formed about four months ago to review
all costs incurred by businessmen in the city, did a comparative
study of costs in Nairobi, Kampala, Harare and Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
In Dar es Salaam, a businessman is charged 300 Tanzanian
shillings (about 0.375 U.S. dollar) per hour, while his
counterpart in Nairobi is paying the equivalent of 50 Tanzanian
shillings (about 0.0625 U.S. dollar), the TCCIA President Elvis
Musiba was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Dar es Salaam City Commission also demands high over the
cost of advertising banners, health inspection and other services.
All these costs add up to the cost of production, said Musiba,
noting that local businessmen are finding it hard to compete in
the East African market.
</P>
<P>
The committee will hold talks with the City Commission and
advise it on reasonable charges to be levied on businessmen for
various services, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: S. Korea, DPRK to Hold Summit in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
will travel to Pyongyang for a historic summit with top leader of
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), Kim Jong Il, on
June 12-14, South Korean Unification Minister Park Jae-kyu
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first-ever summit between the two sides since
the Korean War in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The summit will take place in the form of Kim Jong-il inviting
Kim Dae-jong, and the two sides will hold preparatory contacts
within this month to settle details of the summit, Park told a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
The summit agreement came Saturday after meetings between Park
Jie-won, South Korea's culture and tourism minister, and Song Ho-
gyong, vice chairman of the DPRK's Asia-Pacific Peace Committee in
Shanghai and Beijing, China last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
