<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed sharply higher
in Tokyo Monday, led mainly by high-priced information and
technology issues.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 366.25 points, or 1.81
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 20,619.06.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, surged 39.12 points, or 2.33 percent, to 1,
716.74.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 519.81 million
shares from last Friday's 585.33 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Hitachi was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
After opening the Nikkei rose steadily as rebounds in
information and high-tech issues, combined with Friday's jump in
New York's technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index, improved
market sentiment, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The yen's stabilization against the U.S. dollar was another
factor making investors in Tokyo confident about buying stocks,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Automakers, brokerage houses, chemical firms and retailers also
saw large gains, while air and marine transportation firms,
electric power and gas companies and drug makers were among the
losers.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 874 to 366, with 150 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
