<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Russia to Hold Cooperation Council Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union and Russia
are to meet here on Monday to discuss how to further develop
bilateral relations after the recent presidential elections in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers are expected to meet their Russian
counterpart in the third EU-Russia Cooperation Council meeting,
slated for the end of the first day of the general affairs council
of the EU foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The general affairs council usually lasts two full days.
</P>
<P>
The issues most likely to be discussed among the EU foreign
ministers before meeting Igor Ivanov include the situation in
Chechnya, the outcome of the Russian presidential elections, the
orientation of government policies especially foreign and economic
ones and the coming EU-Russia summit scheduled for May 17 in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama and EU Foreign Policy
High Representative Javier Solana will brief the foreign ministers
on their meeting with Russian president-elect Vladimir Putin and
Foreign Minister Ivanov on April 7 in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are also expected to discuss trade issues such as
Russia's levy on scrap metal exports, regulation of the Russian
market for alcohol beverages and wine, intellectual rights
protection, financial services and overflight rights over Siberia.
</P>
<P>
The EU and Russia will review the progress made in the
implementation of the EU-Russia joint partnership and cooperation
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers are expected to further pressure
Russia on the Chechen issue after the Council of Europe suspended
the voting rights of Russia late last week for alleged
deterioration of the humanitarian situation in the Russian region.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation bloc has been accusing the Russian authorities of
indiscriminate use of forces in Chechnya and warning against a
spillover of the regional conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
