<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: East-West Seeks Win-Win Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The five-day Investment and Trade
Fair for Cooperation Between East and West China closed on Sunday,
clinching contracts worth 100 billion yuan (12 billion U.S.
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The fair was jointly organized by four central government
departments and governments from 19 provinces, autonomous regions
and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The combined value of contracts and investment signed at the
fair was 2.5 times more than the previous session. Over 60 percent
of the contracts were infrastructure, high-tech and tourism
contracts.
</P>
<P>
Jia Zhibang, vice-governor of Shaanxi Province, described the
fair as a win-win cooperation between east and west China under
the strategy of accelerating economic development in western China.
</P>
<P>
Provinces in east China have a wealth of experience in
acquiring market information and commercialization of scientific
achievements while their western partners enjoy rich natural
resources. Cooperation will lead to a leap in western China and a
sustained economic growth in east China.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between east and west China has shifted its focus
from exploiting resources to developing technology, information,
education, tourism and real estate. There has also been a shift
from government-organized to market-oriented economic activities
involving participation of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Businesses in Beijing and Tianjin and Guangdong Province have
signed contracts with their western partners in coal, gas, power,
medicine and agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese economist said, "Development of western China is of
strategic importance. It brings hope to the west and opportunity
to the east. The win-win principle is the basis for east-west
cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
