<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Power Transmission Strategy Paying Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China's strategy of transmitting
electricity from resource-rich western China to power-shortage
coastal areas has achieved initial results.
</P>
<P>
Southwest China's Yunnan Province transmitted 3.7 billion kwh
of electricity to south China's Guangdong Province and Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region in the 1993-1999 period.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has a power generating capacity of 90 million kw,
ranking second in the country. The eight stair hydro-electric
power stations on Lancang River generate 73 billion kwh of
electricity each year, rated as one of the 12 leading hydro-
electric power bases in China.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of Manwan Power Station with an installed
capacity of 1.25 million kw is completed. The first generating
unit of Dachaoshan Power Station, with an installed capacity of 1.
35 million kw, is expected to generate electricity next year.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey, transmission of every kw of electricity
from Yunnan to Guangdong can save 1,120 yuan compared with using
electricity generated in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong consumed 107 billion kwh of electricity last year.
Four billion kwh were imported from Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Zhiqiang, general manager of Yunnan Provincial Power Group,
said the province is able to transmit 1 million kw of electricity
to south China in each flood season by 2005. Its annual
transmission capacity will be tripled by 2017.
</P>
<P>
In addition to providing electricity domestically, Yunnan will
provide Thailand with 3 million kw of electricity a year from 2017,
according to an agreement signed recently between the governments
of China and Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-German Headmaster to Work for "Project Hope" Training Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Manfred Heinrich, a former
German headmaster, has become the first foreigner to engage in
training teachers from Chinese schools funded by Hope Project, a
nationwide charitable program launched in 1990 to help dropouts
resume schooling.
</P>
<P>
Heinrich, about 60, is currently one of the 80 volunteer
lecturers of China's Project Hope Teachers' Training Center.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, this is not Heinrich's first endeavor to
contribute to China's education. He has, since 1996, worked at
Shanghai Teachers' Training Center under a joint program by
Germany's Hanns-Seidel-Stiftung Foundation and the Shanghai
Municipal Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
"I'll exert myself and am ready to contribute more still to
China's significant causes like Project Hope," Heinrich said here
recently.
</P>
<P>
Project Hope has absorbed more than 1.78 billion yuan (214
million US dollars) in donations over the past 10 years, which
have helped Chinese education departments at all levels set up 7,
549 primary schools.
</P>
<P>
More than 2.2 million rural children who dropped out of school
have returned to classrooms thanks to the charitable program.
</P>
<P>
Project Hope will carry out diversified educational programs in
the next five years including efforts to re-train primary school
teachers and spread on-line education and adult education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
