<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Offer Key Research Projects Long-Term Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China plans to offer long-term
science funding to key research projects which are of great
importance to national economic and social development in the
future.
</P>
<P>
China will launch 10 to 15 key science projects from 2001 to
2005, said Chen Jia'er, director of the State Natural Science Fund
Committee (SNSFC).
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to frontier research fields such as high-
tech industries, traditional industrial upgrading and sustainable
development, especially life science, information technology,
resource and environmental sciences, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that funded projects will complement existing
national key science projects, and will push forward academic
exchanges between scientists.
</P>
<P>
SNSFC, established in Beijing in 1986, aims to use research
funds to coordinate and provide funds for research in basic and
applied science in accordance with State policies.
</P>
<P>
China has increased its natural science funding by 20 percent
annually since 1996.
</P>
<P>
China allocated 1.04 billion yuan (about 125 million US dollars)
to natural science research in 1999, compared with 80 million yuan
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
With the support of the Natural Science Fund, China has made
rapid progress in mathematical mechanization theory, distribution
of substances in the universe, modern astrophysics, genome
research and evolution.
</P>
<P>
Among the 60 key basic research projects launched in recent
years in China, 85 percent have received funding from the Natural
Science Fund, according to Chen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
