<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Stresses Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister G.P. Koirala
said his government was committed to going on with the financial
sector reforms to rid the nation of the political and economic
crisis it is facing.
</P>
<P>
While inaugurating the three-day annual meeting of Nepal
Chamber of Commerce late Sunday, Koirala appealed to the private
sector to co-operate with the government to enhance the economic
growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We need to move ahead with a new vision to combat poverty and
develop the nation," said Koirala.
</P>
<P>
"The reform process is very much necessary for the country, and
we cannot retract from this move whatsoever be the result," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said the financial institutions, industry and trade
sectors should target the poor rural populace and support the
government's poverty alleviation program.
</P>
<P>
He reassured the businessmen at the meeting that the government
will also extend full cooperation to solve the problems trade and
industry sector is facing.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking on the occasion, Finance Minister Mahesh Acharya
said that financial sector reform was the first priority of the
government and called for private sector's cooperation to make it
a success.
</P>
<P>
"Financial sector reform is the only way out to rid the nation
of the poverty trap, which is difficult for the government to
accomplish alone," said Acharya, appealing to the private sector
to be equally active.
</P>
<P>
"In order to solve the problem of absolute poverty, we cannot
retract from the process of economic liberalization," he added.
</P>
<P>
Stressing on investment rise to achieve a higher economic
growth, Acharya pledged the government was committed to creating
an investment friendly environment to attract domestic and foreign
investors. 
</P>
