<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Take Move to Discourage Food Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi government is
contemplating measures to discourage imports of foodstuffs,
specially cereals, considering the bumper production of rice in
the country during the last three years, The New Nation reported
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government would soon implement several measures to
decrease food imports with the objectives of saving foreign
exchange and protecting the interest of local farmers, the report
said, adding that the fiscal measures for checking import of rice
may be strengthened and duty on imports of cereals may be further
increased.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the government withdrew all duties on import of
rice during the post-flood period of 1998 in order to encourage
and facilitate procurement of foodstuffs through private sector.
</P>
<P>
The present food stock position, however, is satisfactory, and
with the bumper production of rice in the current situation, the
food supply position would further improve.
</P>
<P>
In such a situation, inflow of huge imported rice and wheat may
deprive farmers of reasonable price of their produces and increase
expenditure of foreign exchange unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
As prices of rice and wheat in the international market have
declined significantly this year, import of rice at lower costs
may adversely affect local production and also returns to farmers,
experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
