<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Not to Phase Out Tariffs As Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
announced here Monday that it will freeze all tariffs at current
levels until at lease July 1, 2005.
</P>
<P>
Acting Minister of Commerce Trevor Mallard said in a statement
that tariff reductions planned by the previous government with the
National Party as its ruling party will not go ahead and the new
New Zealand government formed jointly by the Labor Party and the
Alliance in last December will be moving urgently to repeal the
Tariff(Zero Duty) Amendment ACT 1998, which the previous
government implemented to phase out all tariffs by July 1, 2006.
</P>
<P>
"The coalition government has made it clear that New Zealand
will no longer be removing tariffs on a strictly unilateral basis,
"Mallard said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not see any point in New Zealand leading the world in
this way. We will consider tariff changes where there are clear
benefits to New Zealand," he added.
</P>
<P>
This new policy direction, Mallard noted, is "an important part
of our intention to assist industry development and employment in
New Zealand."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
