<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Tap China's Help in Food Security Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- As part of the efforts to ensure
food security for the Filipinos, President Joseph Estrada plans to
tap China's assistance in modernizing the country's agricultural
system when he visits Beijing this May.
</P>
<P>
The president noted Monday that China's expertise has already
proved valuable in introducing the use of hybrid rice seeds to
Filipino farmers.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said in a statement he hopes to expand agricultural
cooperation between his country and China during his visit to
Beijing next month.
</P>
<P>
"I'll go to China in May to ask for aid in agriculture. Chinese
Premier Zhu Rongji promised to give us help in that area when he
visited us last year," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to the Philippines last November, Zhu proposed
the setting up of a Chinese-Philippine Agriculture Center to mark
the 25th anniversary of establishing diplomatic relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has ordered agriculture and local government officials
to encourage farmers to use hybrid rice seeds developed in China.
</P>
<P>
"This new Chinese technology will be a big help to our farmers.
Their income will almost double when they use these seeds," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed the need for farmers to use new
farming technologies to maximize their productivity.
</P>
<P>
Estrada noted that the Enhanced Rice Action Program (Erap) and
Erap Seed Program, which use these Chinese hybrid seeds, aim to
double the present national average of 2.9 metric tons per hectare
with the planting of hybrid rice.
</P>
<P>
The use of these hybrid seeds, the president believed, would
also help him realize his vision of making the country self-
sufficient in rice by 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
