<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia Allows War Crimes Tribunal to Probe Alleged Mass Grave Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Croatian government Sunday
okayed an investigation by international war crimes tribunal
experts into an alleged mass grave site suspected of containing
the bodies of ethnic Serbs killed by Croatian troops during the
1991-1995 Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the government's information office said that
the decision was made on the basis of international commitments
Croatia shoulders, related laws on cooperation with the
International War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague, the Netherlands,
and other important norms, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the government fixed conditions with the U.N-
sponsored tribunal for its investigations into the possible mass
grave site located in the region of Gospic, about 100 kilometers
southwest of the capital Zagreb, so that Croatia's sovereignty and
legal system can be fully respected.
</P>
<P>
Near the end of the Bosnian war, Croatian troops staged in
Gospic, a Serb-populated region in the former Yugoslav republic, a
storm operation, executing reportedly dozens of Serb civilians and
dumping them in a pit.
</P>
<P>
Since last year the international war crimes court has demanded
participation in digging the site and cooperation from the
Croatian government, including presenting related archives.
</P>
<P>
The death in December 1999 of President Franjo Tudjman, who had
refused to admit that Croats were involved in war crimes, and the
fall of his nationalist party in January elections paved the way
for better cooperation with the tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six CIS Members Vow to Enhance Anti-Terrorism Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMATY, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Members of the CIS Collective
Security Pact Sunday vowed to set up an anti-terrorism center at
the end of a two-day secretaries conference of the security
committees of the pact held in Dushanbe, Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
According to an Interfax report monitored here, participants
discussed measures to enhance the cooperation among the security
committees in the CIS. They placed emphasis on drawing up anti-
terrorism and anti-extremism regulations and an ordinance on
establishing a joint anti-terrorism center.
</P>
<P>
As for the international anti-drug issue, they agreed that
illegal dealing in drugs threatens the social security of every
CIS member. They decided to take more coordination measures to
crack down on drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Presided over by Vladimir Zemsky, secretary general of a
collective security committee of the CIS, the conference was
participated by secretaries of security committees from Russia,
Kazakhstan, Kirghizstan, Armenia, Belarus and representatives from
Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
The CIS collective security pact was signed by the above six
countries in Tashkent on May 15, 1992, but Uzbekistan dropped out
last May.
</P>
<P>
Emomali Sharipovich Rakhmonov, president of Tajikistan, met the
participants before the conference started. 
</P>
</TEXT>
