<HEADLINE> Greece's Ruling Party Wins Parliamentary Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Greece's ruling Panhellenic
Socialist Movement (PASOK) has won Sunday's parliamentary
elections by obtaining 157 seats in the 300-member parliament with
43.7 percent of the votes, followed by the main opposition New
Democracy (ND) with 126 seats and 43 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
After all the ballots were counted on Monday morning, the
Communist Party of Greece is in the third place with 11 seats,
followed by the Coalition of the Left and Progress with 6 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Social Movement will not be represented in
parliament as it harnessed less than 3 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
With more than 8.9 million Greeks flocking to the 18,959
polling stations Sunday, the closest race in recent Greek history,
election officials have reported an unprecedented turnout of more
than 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although a total of 26 political parties participated in the
elections, PASOK and ND are believed to be the two major players.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary elections in Greece are held officially every
four years, and the last elections took place in 1996 with the
ruling PASOK winning 162 seats by obtaining 41.49 percent of the
votes while ND got 108 seats and 38.12 percent of the votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
