<HEADLINE> S. Korea, DPRK to Hold Summit in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
will travel to Pyongyang for a historic summit with top leader of
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), Kim Jong Il, on
June 12-14, South Korean Unification Minister Park Jae-kyu
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the summit will make its mark in the history of
national division as an end to the Cold War of confrontation and a
starting point to creating a new history of reconciliation and
cooperation," Park said.
</P>
<P>
The summit, opening for the first time since the division of
the peninsula, will provide an opportunity to sincerely discuss
the future of the people on the peninsular, Park said.
</P>
<P>
He said the South Korean government will make full preparations
for the success of the summit.
</P>
<P>
The summit will take place in the form of Kim Jong Il inviting
Kim Dae-Jung, and the two sides will hold preparatory contacts
within this month to settle details.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached a summit agreement on Saturday during a
meeting between South Korean Culture and Tourism Minister Park Jie-
won and Song Ho-gyong, vice chairman of the DPRK's Asia-Pacific
Peace Committee, in Beijing, China last month, according to Park.
</P>
<P>
They made their first contact in Shanghai, China, on March 17
after Pyongyang expressed its willingness to open a summit with
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Foreign Affairs and Trade Ministry informed
the summit agreement Sunday to the ambassadors of Japan, China,
Russia and the United States in Seoul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
