<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Major Events on Proposed Inter-Korean Summits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The following is a chronology of
major events related to proposed summits between South Korea and
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
-- January, 12 1981: South Korean President Chun Doo-hwan
suggests mutual visits of South Korean and DPRK presidents in his
New Year's speech.
</P>
<P>
-- June 5, 1981: Chun suggests direct talks between South
Korean and DPRK leaders in opening address to the Advisory Council
of Democratic and Peaceful Unification.
</P>
<P>
-- July 1, 1981: DPRK President Kim Il Sung rejects Chun's
offers.
</P>
<P>
-- February 25, 1988: President Roh Tae-woo expresses intention
to hold dialogue with Kim Il-sung in his presidential inauguration
speech.
</P>
<P>
-- August 15, 1988: Roh suggests talks with Kim Il Sung in his
Liberation Day speech.
</P>
<P>
-- October 18, 1988: Roh voices his intention to visit
Pyongyang in his speech at U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
-- February. 25, 1993: South Korean President Kim Young-sam
suggests a summit with Kim Il-sung in his presidential
inauguration speech.
</P>
<P>
-- May 25, 1993: DPRK Prime Minister Kang Song San suggests
inter-Korean summit through exchanges of special envoys in his
message to Seoul.
</P>
<P>
-- Febraury 25, 1994: Kim Young-sam declares that he will push
for inter-Korean summit irrespective of the North's nuclear
program.
</P>
<P>
-- June 16-17, 1994: Kim Il Sung accepts proposal on bilateral
talks with Kim Young-sam.
</P>
<P>
-- June 18, 1994: Kim Young-sam agrees to inter-Korean summit.
</P>
<P>
-- July 8, 1994: The scheduled summit is canceled due to Kim Il
Sung's sudden death.
</P>
<P>
-- February 25, 1998: President Kim Dae-jung proposed to
exchange special envoys between Seoul and Pyongyang to implement
inter-Korean basic agreement.
</P>
<P>
-- August 15, 1998: Kim Dae-jung proposes to establish channels
for inter-Korean dialogue and to send a special envoy to the North.
</P>
<P>
-- February 3, 1999: DPRK proposes high-level inter-Korean
political talks.
</P>
<P>
-- March 10, 2000: President Kim Dae-jung announces "Berlin
Declaration" calling for the inter-Korean official economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- March 17, 2000: Delegates of Seoul and Pyongyang hold first
contact in Shanghai on the summit between Kim Dae-jung and Kim
Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
-- April 1, 2000: President Kim Dae-jung mentions special
economic demands from the DPRK after the general elections April
13.
</P>
<P>
-- April 8, 2000: South Korean Culture and Tourism Minister
Park Jie-won and vice chairman of DPRK Asia-Pacific Committee
agree in Beijing on an inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang on June 12-
14.
</P>
<P>
-- April 10, 2000: Both Seoul and Pyongyang announce holding of
the inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang on June 12-14.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
