<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Toronto Blazed After Blasts in Chemical Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 firefighters are still
battling a fierce blaze in Toronto after a series of explosions
rocked a chemical plant Sunday afternoon in the city's east.
</P>
<P>
There have been no reports of casualties, but authorities
warned that further explosions are possible as the fire is
engulfing the plant containing tanks of flammable liquids.
</P>
<P>
CTV television quoted a firefighter as saying that they had
difficulty in approaching the fire because of the black smoke,
while another witness said that the blaze is too hot for anybody
to get near the site.
</P>
<P>
Huge black fumes were rising hundreds of meters high and could
be seen from as far as 20 kilometers away during the day, said the
CTV.
</P>
<P>
A small population east of the plant was already evacuated,
while rail traffic by the side of the plant was halted.
</P>
<P>
This is the second fire reported to occur in the plant, which
produces driveway sealers, caulking products and other building
materials. The plant had tanks of xylene, a volatile hydrocarbon
used as a solvent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
