<HEADLINE> Japan Welcomes Inter-Korean Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Japan on Monday welcomed the news
that leaders of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
and South Korea will hold their first-ever summit in Pyongyang in
June.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori praised the accord,
describing it "the fruit of untiring effort" by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is very good for peace in Asia as well," Mori told
reporters at his official residence.
</P>
<P>
Chief Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki told a press conference that
he believes the summit, if realized, will have "a very good impact
" on the talks between Tokyo and Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the DPRK Friday ended their ninth round of
negotiations to normalize diplomatic relations in Pyongyang
without breakthrough. They agreed to meet again in late May.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Yohei Kono, in a statement issued
shortly after Pyongyang and Seoul announced the agreement earlier
Monday, said the accord was of "epoch-making significance."
</P>
<P>
"We welcome and will fully support it," Kono said, adding that
he believes the accord showed the will of the two governments to
promote dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK media and South Korean government announced earlier in
the day that DPRK leader Kim Jong Il and South Korean President
Kim Dae-jung will hold a summit on June 12-14 in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
The summit will be the first ever between the two sides since
the Korean War in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached on Saturday in Beijing, China,
South Korea and the DPRK will have a preliminary contact this
month to make arrangements for the summit, both sides said Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
