<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Wins Sixth Women's World Hockey Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada defeated the United States
Sunday to win its sixth straight title for Women's World Hockey
Championship.
</P>
<P>
Team Canada beat Team U.S.A. 3-2 with Canadian player Nancy
Drolet's goal 6:50 into overtime to give Canada a come-from-behind
victory in Mississauga, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
Drolet picked up the puck on the right boards, skated to the
faceoff circle and blasted the puck off the left shoulder of U.S.
goaltender Sara DeCosta.
</P>
<P>
It popped in the air and floated into the net behind DeCosta,
as 4,890 hockey fans at the Hershey Center erupted for the
decisive score.
</P>
<P>
The win allowed Canada to have a perfect record of 30-0 in team
sport history since the women's tournament was first held in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Finland took the bronze medal with a 7-1
win over Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The Swedes' lack of discipline was their downfall as Finland
scored three power-play goals. The Finns scored two minutes into
the game on a power play and stayed in control the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
Finnish goaltender Tuula Puputti stopped 19 of 20 shots, while
Lotta Gothesson turned away 41 of 48 for Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
