<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Opens 20 Unclimbed Peaks to Mountaineers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- India has opened up 20
unclimbed peaks to mountaineers in the Himalayas, as well as 176
other summits in previously closed border areas, the Indian
Mountaineering Foundation said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Foundation director Colonel Ravindra Nath said that the 20
virgin peaks were mostly bordering neighbouring China and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He added that their heights ranged from 6,000 to 7,800 meters.
</P>
<P>
"The decision will help in promoting tourism and creating jobs
for locals who serve as guides, porters and other service
providers," Nath said.
</P>
<P>
He said the newly opened peaks were located in the northern
Himalayan states of Kashmir, Himachal Pradesh and Uttar Pradesh,
and Sikkim and Arunachal Pradesh in India far-east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
