<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Tourism Popular in NE China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Simplified overseas tourism
procedures and increased per capita income have inspired more and
more Chinese people to travel to foreign countries instead of
sightseeing just around the country.
</P>
<P>
"I will spend my honeymoon in southeast Asia," said Li Xiao'ou,
coming out of the China Travel Agency Shenyang Office.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks will be enough for a Chinese resident to get a
tourist visa now, hard to imagine just several years ago.
</P>
<P>
Statistics with the Shenyang Tourism Bureau (STB), northeast
China's Liaoning Province, show that nearly 20,000 local people
went traveling overseas in 1999, as compares with only several
thousand in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Longer holidays and increase of income have enabled people to
shift their focus to traveling abroad," said Yan Baomin, a STB
official. The per capita GDP last year for Shenyang was as much as
1,700 U.S. dollars. 4,000 to 5,000 local residents traveled
overseas during the seven-day Spring Festival Holiday this
February, almost doubling that the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
March, once a slack period for tourism, now sees increasing
numbers of people at China Tourism Agency Shenyang Office. Middle-
class and private entrepreneurs make up the bulk of the travelers.
Parents going abroad at the expense of their children has also
accounted for a large proportion, said STB officials.
</P>
<P>
Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand, Hong Kong, and Macao, have been
the first choices for travelers." It is worthwhile to have a look
at Singapore, Malaysia, and Thailand in ten days with some 5,000
yuan (about 600 U.S. dollars)," said Li Xiao'ou, adding that 5,000
yuan was just two or three months salary.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics in 1999, some 1.933 million Chinese
people traveled overseas, 66.9 percent more than in 1998, or 67.1
percent of all the Chinese people going abroad that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds World's Largest Liquified Ethylene Gas Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Jiangnan Shipyard (Group) Co.
, Ltd., a major shipyard in Shanghai, has just launched a ship
with a carrying capacity load of 22,000 cubic meters of liquified
ethylene gas.
</P>
<P>
The vessel, "Navigator Mars", is the first of the five
liquified ethylene gas ships ordered by the Navigator Gas Limited
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The ship, 170 meters long and 24.2 meters wide, is equipped
with four liquified gas containers, which can also carries other
kinds of liquified gas like liquified butane gas.
</P>
<P>
Experts say ships used to carry liquified gas are normally made
according to higher quality standards than those for building
ordinary ones because liquified gas is usually combustible,
explosive and highly corrosive.
</P>
<P>
Jiangnan Shipyard is scheduled to deliver the other four
vessels to the U.S. company within this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
