<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Trade-Related News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major trade-related
news in China over the past week are as follows:
</P>
<P>
 Sino-U.S. Trade Ties
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin Thursday urged the United
States to properly handle the issue of granting China permanent
normal trade relations (PNTR), in meeting with visiting U.S.
Commerce Secretary William Daley Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The proper solution to the PNTR issue "is in the interests of
both China and the U.S.," Jiang said. The mutual granting of the
most-favored nation status forms "one of the essential principles
of the World Trade Organization," he pointed out. "China will, as
always, make an active contribution to the healthy development of
the world economy and trade," he added.
</P>
<P>
-- China and the United States began their first meeting on
commerce and trade here Friday since signing a bilateral agreement
on China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO) last
November.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley and Chinese Minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) Shi Guangsheng
co-chaired the 13th session of the China-U.S. Joint Commission on
Commerce and Trade.
</P>
<P>
-- MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng and visiting U.S. Commerce
Secretary William M. Daley Friday issued a joint statement in the
wake of the conclusion of the 13th Session of the China-U.S. Joint
Commission on Commerce and Trade.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley said here Friday
that the U.S. government is making great efforts to see that PNTR
with China is passed by the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
"We are working very, very hard," he told reporters following
the conclusion of the 13th session of the Sino-U.S. Joint
Commission on Commerce and Trade.
</P>
<P>
-- A survey over 130 United States companies in China conducted
by the American Chamber of Commerce in China (ACCC) shows that 88
percent of the companies will expand their businesses in China.
</P>
<P>
-- Tim Stratford, chairman of the ACCC, said recently that the
ACCC will try its best to convince both countries that China's
entry into the WTO tallies with their mutual interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
