<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Trade-Related News (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- State Councilor Wu Yi and Cumhur Ersumer, visiting Turkish
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Energy and Natural Resources,
held talks Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both sides exchanged views on further enhancing bilateral trade
and economic cooperation, and increasing cooperation in the field
of energy.
</P>
<P>
-- China and Russia will enhance shipping cooperation on the
rivers on their borders, according to the 42nd regular meeting of
the Sino-Russian Joint Commission on Border River Shipping, which
was held here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to delineate the courses of the border
rivers, improve shipping conditions, and maintain the stability
and prosperity of the border areas.
</P>
<P>
-- State Councilor Wang Zhongyu met last Monday with Dieter
Zetsche, director and president of commercial vehicles of
DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
-- China and the European Union (EU) will resume their talks on
China's WTO entry, Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi said at the
regular press conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
-- China has recently called for strengthening the precautions
against the possible importation of infected birds and related
products from Italy.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Investment in China
</P>
<P>
-- Netease, one of the most popular Chinese websites, has
established cooperative relations with the US-based BEA System to
develop e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S.-based Internet company Mail.com will set up a joint
venture with the Chinese Internet firm Elong.com to expand
business in the Asian market, the Economic Information Daily
reported last Monday.
</P>
<P>
-- The US-based WI Harper Group Monday said that it will raise
funds of more than 500 million US dollars to invest in e-commerce
and Internet-related industries in Asian areas.
</P>
<P>
-- Dangdang.com, the largest Chinese on-line bookstore in the
world, Tuesday announced that it has obtained new investment from
the Softbank. The shareholders of Dangdang include the
International Digital Group (IDG) and the Kewen Corporation.
</P>
<P>
