<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tapping Western Wells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Developing China's west requires
the efficient use of resources and the application of science,
said Tian Fengshan, China's new Minister of Land and Resources.
</P>
<P>
The 59-year-old former governor of northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province was appointed to the post last month, and
has just returned from a fact-finding tour of western China.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, Tian refuted a widespread
argument that the west's resources, such as land, water and
minerals, will not aid in its development. Some people think poor
transportation and geological conditions, plus ignorance about the
distributions of resources and reserves, will cause developers to
work twice as hard as normal for half the expected gains.
</P>
<P>
Their arguments do not change the importance of using the west'
s resources. A key resource is time, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"The west's development is not a business of several days,"
Tian said. "Considering that it took 20 years for our
traditionally better developed east to advance to today's stage,
the development of western China might take a period at least no
shorter."
</P>
<P>
Although it might take more time, more money and more effort to
use the west's resources, Tian said, these issues need not
discourage anyone.
</P>
<P>
And transportation, geography and other technical concerns are
major targets of the improvement itself.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the minister confirmed some experts'
worries that a water shortage may limit the west development.
</P>
<P>
However, Tian still believes the resources of western China
could become the country's major sources of energy and raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
Another key resource is smart efficiency, he said. "What people
should really strive for is to ensure a scientific and highly
efficient use of the resources."
</P>
<P>
"We should not take the old road of developing an area at the
cost of resource waste and pollution, but rather economize
resources," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Disburse Loans to Indonesia Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund (
IMF) is expected to disburse 400 million U.S. dollars in loans to
Indonesia later this month, according to Cabinet Secretary
Marsillam Simanjuntak.
</P>
<P>
He said an IMF team would come to Jakarta on April 21 to review
the implementation of economic reform programs promised by the
government in January.
</P>
<P>
The result of the review would be sent to the IMF executive
board at its headquarters in Washington to decide on the second-
tranche disbursement from the IMF 5 billion dollars bailout fund
for Indonesia for the 2000-2002 period.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that one week after the visit of the review team, the
IMF will disburse the money," Simanjuntak was quoted by the
Jakarta Post Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, IMF chief representative in Jakarta John Dodsworth
said late last month that even though the review could be
completed in the first half of April, the second disbursement of
loans would probably take place only in mid-May at the soonest.
</P>
<P>
"After the review, it needs about three weeks until the IMF
executive board in Washington can meet," Dodsworth said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government signed a letter of intent with the
IMF on January 20, in which it promised to complete a host of
ambitious economic measures by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
But many of the key programs were not completed by the deadline,
prompting the IMF to delay the disbursement of the 400 million
dollars, which had been scheduled for April 4.
</P>
<P>
Simanjuntak said that Coordinating Minister for Economy,
Finance and Industry Kwik Kian Gie handed over to President
Abdurrahman Wahid on Friday night a document reporting that 42
items of the letter had been implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
