<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat stepped up pressure
on Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Sunday as the peace talks
remained static, saying Barak would fall if he lets people down in
peace-making with Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Barak would fall as his right-wing predecessor Benjamin
Netanyahu if he fails to make peace with Arabs, Arafat said,
quoted by Egypt's Middle East News Agency. (Egypt-Palestinians-
Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- A nuclear power station in Kent, southeast England,
was evacuated Sunday and an emergency was declared after a leak of
carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
Dungeness B, on the coast near Romney, was at the center of an
alert for several hours until the all-clear was given.
</P>
<P>
Officials said there was no risk of a nuclear leak and no
danger to the reactor because it had been switched off for
maintenance since November. (Britain-Nuclear)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia will continue helping the United States
hunt down the Saudi exile Osama bin Laden, who was blamed by the U.
S. for masterminding the 1998 bombings of two U.S. embassies in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The issue of bin Laden was touched upon during the talks in
Riyadh on Sunday between Saudi crown prince Abdullah bin Abdul-
Aziz and visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen. (Saudi
Arabia-US-Cohen)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh has said that
Damascus is ready to compromise on sharing water resources with
Israel in a bid to break the deadlock of peace talks, Egyptian
newspapers reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
While Syria refuses to compromise on land, it is ready to
negotiate a deal on sharing the Sea of Galilee, Shareh was quoted
as telling the Egyptian newspapers after meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on Saturday in Cairo. (Syria-Israel-Water)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Peru will hold a second round of presidential election,
according to the preliminary results of parts of polling stations
in the Andean country Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Moments after the voting ended, an exit poll by the independent
polling firm Apoyo gave 54-year-old Alejandro Toledo 48.5 percent
of the votes to President Fujimori's 42.7 percent. (Peru-Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece's ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK)
is maintaining a slight, but steady, lead over the main opposition
New Democracy (ND) in Sunday's parliamentary elections, with 78.8
percent of the votes counted nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures released around 1:55 a.m. Monday show the
PASOK leading with 43.6 percent, with the ND posting 43.1 percent.
(Greece-Elections)  
</P>
