<HEADLINE> UEFA: Leeds' Plan to Ban Turkish Fans 'Makes Sense' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- European soccer's governing body
UEFA on Sunday gave support to Leeds United's plan to ban
Galatasaray fans from their UEFA Cup semifinal second leg after
two English supporters were killed in Istanbul last week.
</P>
<P>
UEFA spokesman Frits Ahlstroem said the proposal, put forward
because of security reasons, "made a lot of sense", adding a final
ruling about the game on April 20 would be made on Monday or
Tuesday, according to the Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
Leeds want the ban on away supporters because they are worried
about retaliatory violence after two of their fans were stabbed to
death during trouble 24 hours before Thursday's first leg which
they lost 2-0.
</P>
<P>
"It made a lot of sense to us because it's a question of making
everybody at Elland Road safe for the second leg,"Ahlstroem was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"That's why we fully understood if Leeds United can't guarantee
the security. This is something special in this situation and we
have full understanding for that."
</P>
<P>
UEFA have already sent a letter to both clubs telling them it
would be better for the game to be played without Turkish
supporters. They are waiting for official responses from both
clubs, expected on Monday, before announcing their ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
