<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Ready to Negotiate Water Deal with Israel: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh
has said that Damascus is ready to compromise on sharing water
resources with Israel in a bid to break the deadlock of peace
talks, Egyptian newspapers reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
While Syria refuses to compromise on land, it is ready to
negotiate a deal on sharing the Sea of Galilee, Shareh was quoted
as telling the Egyptian newspapers after meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on Saturday in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Syria demands that Israel completely withdraw from the Golan
Heights, a strategic plateau Israel occupied in the 1967 Mideast
War, in return for peace.
</P>
<P>
Shareh told reporters that land is not negotiable, but water is.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since January
due to disputes over the Golan Heights. Damascus conditions its
return to the negotiating table on an advance Israeli commitment to
a complete Israeli exit from the Golan.
</P>
<P>
Water is another thorny issue linked to the argument over the
border between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants Israel to withdraw to the cease-fire line prior to
the 1967 war, which would give Syria control of the northeastern
shore of the Sea of Galilee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
