<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Trade Deficit Rises by 143.5 Percent: Bank Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's trade deficit in
February this year registered a sharp increase by 143.5 percent
over January, a Tanzania's central bank report said over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
During the month, deficit in the trade account grew to 52.1
million U.S. dollars from 21.4 million U.S. dollars recorded in
the previous month, the Bank of Tanzania said in its monthly
economic review for March.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the poor performance of the trade
account to 37.5 percent increase in imports, surpassing a 2.2
percent increase in exports.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, imports in February rose to 117.8
million U.S. dollars from 85.7 million U.S. dollars in January.
</P>
<P>
The export increase of 2.2 percent from 64.3 million U.S.
dollars in January to 65.7 million U.S. dollars in February was
due to an increase in non-traditional exports such as petroleum
products, manufactured goods, fish and fish produce.
</P>
<P>
Report said export earnings in February amounted to 65.7
million U.S. dollars and imports totaled 11.8 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in traditional exports was partly due to decline
in export values and export unit prices for all traditional
commodities except cotton and tea, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
