<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Batch of Iraqi POWs Back Home From Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGDHAD, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The third batch of 500 Iraqi
prisoners of war (POWs) released by Iran on Monday crossed the
Iranian-Iraqi border and set foot on Iraqi soil, the Iraqi News
Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
It was just another tearful reunion. Many POWs wept with joy,
while their family members, overwhelmed by excitement and rejoice,
threw flowers and candies on them.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people have been waiting for their arrival in the
border region, said the INA, adding that many POWs have not been
able to see their loved ones for as long as 18 years.
</P>
<P>
Iran on Sunday morning unilaterally released 500 Iraqi POWs left
over from the 1980-88 bloody war between the two neighbors, and it
set free another batch of 500 on Sunday night. In all, 1,500 Iraqi
POWs have since been back home.
</P>
<P>
The fourth batch of 500 Iraqi POWs are expected to arrive in
Iraq on Tuesday, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Red Crescent Society has done its best to ensure that
all the returned POWs can receive best medical services, said the
INA.
</P>
<P>
The POWs have been hailed as heroes by the Iraqi government and
each POW will be given 300,000 Iraqi dinars (150 U.S. dollars) for
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
Iran announced last Wednesday to unilaterally release 2,000
Iraqi
POWs in a bid to solve the POWs issue with Iraq, one of the major
hurdles on the way of normalization of Tehran-Baghdad ties.
</P>
<P>
Iranian officials expressed hope that Baghdad would respond to
Tehran's "goodwill gesture" by helping to determine the fate of
Iranian POWs and those missing in action.
</P>
<P>
Iraq claimed that Iran is still holding more than 13,000 Iraqi
POWs, while Tehran claimed last month that Iraq still holds 2,800
Iranians according to available documents.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been exchanging POWs in recent years in a
bid to improve strained relations.
</P>
<P>
Iran said that it had released 55,438 Iraqi POWs since 1981 on
103 occasions while Iraq freed 39,417 Iranian POWs in the same
period on 70 occasions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges Stepped-up Efforts to Advance Mideast Peace March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Egypt called on Monday for stepped-
up efforts to break the deadlock in the Middle East peace process
and push it forward "as quickly as possible."
</P>
<P>
"There is not ... any breakthrough, or any development" in the
Arab-Israeli peace negotiations, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said following a meeting between Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Instead, "there is a problem and there is a crisis" in the peace
march, Moussa said while briefing reporters on the Mubarak-Barak
talks, which the minister said dwelt on the situation on the
Syrian, Palestinian and Lebanese tracks.
</P>
<P>
Barak stopped over in Cairo en route to a summit meeting on
Tuesday with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"At present, which is very crucial for all of us, (we should) be
serious with the peace process and move as quickly as possible,"
Moussa stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since January
due to Israel's refusal to commit itself to withdrawal from the
Golan Heights the Jewish state occupied in the 1967 Mideast war,
and control of the Sea of Galilee at the foot of the heights.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations are underway at a secluded
air force base near Washington. But the negotiations are as what
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said "a mere chat" in lack of
progress. Clinton has also invited Arafat to a summit meeting on
April 20 in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
