<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes North-South Koreas Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday welcomed the announcement of a summit between the
Democratic People's Republic of Korean and the Republic of Korea,
saying it was "fundamental to solving the problems of the Korean
Peninsula."
</P>
<P>
"I welcome the announcement that the Republic of Korea and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea will hold an historic first
summit in June," White House spokesman Joe Lockhart read the
president statement. "Direct dialogue between the two Koreas is
something we have long advocated and is fundamental to solving the
problems of the Korean Peninsula. This announcement is testimony
to the wisdom and long-term vision of President Kim Dae-jung's
engagement policy. I congratulate both leaders on their decision
to meet."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also called South Korean
Foreign Minister Lee Joung-binn Monday to convey her strong
support for the announcement.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary Albright called Foreign Minister Lee of South Korea
early this morning to convey our strong support for this
announcement and to offer our continued close coordination to
ensure a successful summit," State Department spokesman James
Rubin said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
"It's been our view for some time that the central issue of
peace and stability in the Korean Peninsula cannot be resolved
without direct dialogue," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the summit was released Sunday
simultaneously in both capitals, which said President Kim Dae-jung
will travel to Pyongyang on June 12-14 for a historic summit at
the invitation of Kim Jong-il, the DPRK's top leader.
</P>
<P>
The United States itself also has held several meetings with
DPRK officials for an arrangement of the first high-level visit by
a DPRK official to Washington for reciprocation of a trip by U.S.
presidential envoy William Perry and State Department Counselor
Wendy Sherman last May.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the visit was still being discussed but had not been
brought any closer by the announcement of the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
