<HEADLINE> U.S. Vows to Keep Forces in Korean Peninsula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States, while
welcoming the announcement of the North-south Koreas summit, vowed
on Monday it would keep its forces on the Korean Peninsula even if
the two Koreas reach any positive agreement.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin argued that the U.S.
forces, currently 37,000 strong, stationed in South Korea for a
half-century since the Korean War early in the 1950s, was "
justified" despite strong opposition from the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea, which says the U.S. deployment was the cause of
tension in the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"From our standpoint, our deployment of forces and troops and
equipment in South Korea was justified by the historical situation
there," Rubin said. "That remains our view."
</P>
<P>
"I'm not aware of any changes in those plans," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the White House said in a statement that President
Bill Clinton welcomed the announcement of a summit between the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea and the Republic of Korea,
saying it was "fundamental to solving the problems of the Korean
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"Direct dialogue between the two Koreas is something we have
long advocated and is fundamental to solving the problems of the
Korean Peninsula," Clinton said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also called South Korean
Foreign Minister Lee Joung-binn on Monday to convey her strong
support for the announcement.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary Albright called Foreign Minister Lee of South Korea
early this morning to convey our strong support for this
announcement and to offer our continued close coordination to
ensure a successful summit," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"It's been our view for some time that the central issue of
peace and stability in the Korean Peninsula cannot be resolved
without direct dialogue," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the summit was released on Sunday
simultaneously in both capitals, which said President Kim Dae-jung
will travel to Pyongyang on June 12-14 for a historic summit at
the invitation of Kim Jong-il, the DPRK's top leader.
</P>
<P>
The United States itself also has held several meeting with
DRPK's officials for an arrangement of the first high-level visit
by a DPRK official to Washington for reciprocation of a trip by U.
S. presidential envoy William Perry and State Department Counselor
Wendy Sherman last May.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the visit was still being discussed but had not been
brought any closer by the announcement of the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
