<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Allow Pubs Open 24 Hours a Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Pubs in England and Wales would be
allowed to stay open 24 hours a day under plans for the biggest
shake-up in licensing laws for almost a century.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw published a White Paper on Monday
setting out proposals to end fixed closing times for pubs
alongside increased powers for the police to close down premises
which become associated with violence caused by drunken customers.
</P>
<P>
Under the plans, people convicted of violent behavior in pubs
could be banned for life from licensed premises, while "habitual
drunkards" could be banned from buying drink for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The proposals would end Sunday restrictions and give children
more access to pubs and bars.
</P>
<P>
They also include plans to transfer the issuing of licenses from
magistrates courts to local authorities and a new system of
personal licenses which would allow holders to sell alcohol from
any building.
</P>
<P>
The White Paper is aimed at streamlining rules drawn up during
the First World War.
</P>
<P>
Pub landlords would be able to decide on their own hours, with
the aim of staggering closing times between 11 pm and 3 am, with
some premises allowed to stay open all night, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
But licensing authorities will take account of local concerns
before granting licenses.
</P>
<P>
The White Paper's proposals are unlikely to be implemented
before the general election, as the government seeks responses to
the plans before bringing forward legislation in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Licensing laws in England and Wales have changed little since
1915, when they were tightened to stop factory workers turning up
drunk and harming the war effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000410.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Boost Tourism Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
will spend 1.75 million euro (about 1.68 million U.S. dollars)
provided by the European Union in implementing a ten-year
integrated tourism market master plan (TMMP) to be launched this
June.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions in the parliament which is in session
in Tanzania's central town of Dodoma, Minister for Tourism and
Natural Resources Zakia Megji said the fund, which was allocated
to Tanzania through the Lome Convention Arrangement, will be used
to implement tourism policy, grade tourist hotels, improve data
collection for planned tourism data bank and strengthen the
tourism department.
</P>
<P>
The money will also be used to purchase equipment and logistics
for the project implementation and to prepare a zonal-based
implementation plan, she said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is a booming industry in Tanzania. The country earned
last year a total of 11.2 billion shillings (about 14 million U.S.
dollars) from receiving 482,000 foreign tourists who came to
sample tourist attractions ranging from wild animals to
geographical features like Mount Kilimanjaro, the highest peak in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that tourism currently contributes
to 18.5 percent of the country's gross domestic product and 50
percent of its annual foreign exchange earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
