<HEADLINE> Zambian Minister Warns of Disintegration of Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Environment Minister and
presidential hopeful Ben Mwila said here on Monday that the
country's ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) is
heading for a disaster and will soon disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, MMD National Treasurer, told state-run Zambia News
Agency that the party will vanish and go under.
</P>
<P>
He urged MMD leaders to learn the art of dialog if they want
the party to survive and remain intact for the 2001 general
elections.
</P>
<P>
People should sit down as a party and talk to iron out the
problems the party is facing at the moment, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the current expulsions and suspension do not
auger well for the party.
</P>
<P>
Mwila described his working relationship with other cabinet
ministers as cordial and said he is still consulting on the issue
of him standing as president.
</P>
<P>
He said he has to go around the country to measure his
popularity, adding that a lot of leaders in the MMD are also
campaigning for presidency in the name of consulting.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, he will make his position known
after consulting and will wait for the MMD National Executive
Committee (NEC) to air his views.
</P>
<P>
MMD announced here on April 2 that its Information and
Publicity Secretary George Mwambazi and Lusaka Province
Chairperson for Women's Affairs Rose Zimba had been expelled from
the party for alleged disobeying party regulations.
</P>
<P>
They were expelled from the party following dark corner
meetings they had been holding in support of Mwila together with
some other party members who had also been campaigning for Mwila,
said Lusaka Province Minister Sonny Mulenga.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, one of the country's richest with a business empire
spanning manufacturing, construction, finance and fertilizers,
helped Frederick Chiluba defeat former President Kenneth Kaunda in
the 1991 elections and now is seen as a leading candidate to
replace Chiluba in the next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
But Chiluba said last September that he would ensure that his
uncle Mwila does not become the country's president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
