<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Strengthen Control Over Firearms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
will pass a bill to impose stricter control over firearms in the
country, said South African Safety and Security Minister Steve
Tshwete on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Firearms Control Bill, which is currently before the South
African National Assembly, will provide stricter control over the
issuing and renewal of firearms licences to individuals as well as
stricter control over state-owned firearms, Tshwete said at the
United Nations' 10th Congress on Crime and Justice in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Accord to a report by the South African Press Association, he
told the delegates that more resources have been made available to
 the South African police so that gun trafficking will be
combated.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has undertaken operations with its
 neighboring countries to find and destroy caches of arms left
over from wars, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the easy availability of guns in
South Africa contributes largely to the country's high crime rate.
</P>
<P>
Most guns used in crime were either stolen from private owners
or the amy or were firearms that had been lost, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
