<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges to Reduce Greenhouse Gas Emissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government Monday
urged the southern African region to reduce greenhouse gas
emissions in order to set off the likely effects of climatic
change.
</P>
<P>
The region is vulnerable to climatic change with the latest one
hitting Mozambique, which this year suffered the worst floods in
50 years, said Zambian Environment and Natural Resources Minister
Ben Mwila.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the region must play a role in reducing the
greenhouse gas emissions, the minister said while opening a
five-day workshop here on climatic change for government planning
officials.
</P>
<P>
He said climatic change studies in Zambia have addressed
various issues such as greenhouse gas emissions with a view to
reduce the emissions.
</P>
<P>
He urged the private sector to work in close collaboration with
the government to come up with a project to develop the climatic
change program because Zambia, and the southern African region as
a whole, lacks financial resources, technology and adequate
infrastructure to detect and deal with major climatic changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
