<HEADLINE> Johannesburg Sets Up Surveillance Cameras to Detect Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The South African major city
of Johannesburg has been equipped with a network of surveillance
cameras as authorities act to quell rampant crimes on the city's
streets.
</P>
<P>
The four-million-rand (600,000 U.S. dollars) monitoring unit
represents a joint effort of local government, police and some
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The 12 surveillance cameras have been placed at hot spots in
the city center and will be able to track the movements of any
person within range, the South African Press Association reported
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The cameras, which can zoom on people two kilometers away, will
be linked by fibre-optic cable to a 24-hour control room, where
they will be operated by specially trained operators.
</P>
<P>
When the cameras were installed in cities of Cape Town and
Durban, crime was slashed by about 80 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
