<HEADLINE> S. Africa Calls for International Cooperation in Fighting Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Monday urged
the international community to find workable and credible
solutions to strengthen their common efforts to combat crime.
</P>
<P>
Since crime transcends national boundaries, crime prevention
requires international co-operation and coordinated strategies,
said South African Justice Minister Penuell Maduna after he was
elected president of the United Nations' 10th Congress on Crime
and Justice.
</P>
<P>
Maduna was quoted by the South African Press Association as
saying that " the fight against crime goes beyond the issues of
law and order. It goes to the core of a just and democratic
society."
</P>
<P>
Technological advances have made crime more complex and opened
up more opportunities for criminals, he said, adding that crime
affects different countries in different ways.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South African National Director of Public
Prosecutions Bulelani Ngcuka said there is more pressure on the
criminal justice systems in societies in transition than in
settled democracies.
</P>
<P>
While there is a need to establish a human rights culture in
emerging democracies, the need to establish and maintain an
effective justice system should not be ignored, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
