<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Nigerian Opposition Leader Back From Exile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Anthony Enahoro, a prominent former
 opposition leader of Nigeria, Monday returned to his home country
after four years in exile in the United States.
</P>
<P>
He was greeted as a hero in Lagos, the largest city in the west
African country. Among those going to the airport to welcome him
were thousands of supporters including two state governors.
</P>
<P>
Enahoro was one of the founding fathers of new Nigeria, who
fought tirelessly to press Britain to accept Nigeria's
independence in October, 1960.
</P>
<P>
His chequered political history included a stint as
commissioner (minister) for information, culture, youth, sports,
co-operatives and labor during the period from 1967 to 1974.
</P>
<P>
Noted for his belief in justice, equity and the rule of law,
Enahoro, along with other eminent Nigerians, formed the Nigeria
Association for Democracy to protest the military annulment of the
1993 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Enahoro was briefly detained in 1994 by the regime of late
military leader Sani Abacha, before he fled the country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately clear if the former opposition leader
still has energy for Nigeria's rigorous politics. 
</P>
