<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Falls Sharply But Dow Rises on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell sharply Monday as investors were worried
about the tech firms in forthcoming first quarter earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
At the close of session, the Nasdaq index fell 258.25 at 4,188.
20, its second largest drop ever.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 75.08 at 11,186.56 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index fell 11.89 at 1,504.46.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq index fell as Richard McCabe, chief market analyst
at Merrill Lynch, told clients in a research note that they should
reduce their exposure to technology stocks in favor of energy,
financial and consumer issues. Microsoft, Applied Materials and
Yahoo! fell.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations coincided with remarks from a number of
Wall Street strategists in recent weeks that strongest earnings
growth this quarter is expected not from the technology sector,
but from the less heralded energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The recent wild rides in the technology stocks dragged the
Nasdaq index down 349.15 points Monday, last week and 574.57
points before marching back on the following day. But the
composite rebounded in the three consecutive sessions after the
volatility.
</P>
<P>
The Dow index rose as investors drew out some tech stocks and
moved money into more stable and predictable Old Economy stocks.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 0.28 at 659.71. But American Stock Exchange
index fell 30.65 at 958.04 and the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies fell 24.33 at 518.66.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,618 down, 1,386 up and 464
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 850.18 million shares from 888.41
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
